# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ashoka
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] The **1959 Tibetan uprising** or **Lhasa uprising** began on 10 March 1959 as a series of protests in the Tibetan capital of Lhasa, fueled by fears that the government of the People's Republic of China planned to arrest the Dalai Lama.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Over the next ten days, the demonstrations evolved from expressions of support for the 14th Dalai Lama to demands for independence and the reversal of the 1951 Chinese annexation of Tibet.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] After protesters acquired weapons, China's People's Liberation Army (PLA) shelled protesters in the Dalai Lama's summer palace and deployed tanks to suppress the demonstrations.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Bloody fighting continued for the next three days while the Dalai Lama escaped to India.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Thousands of Tibetans were killed during the 1959 uprising, but the exact number is disputed.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] The CIA provided extensive support to the uprising, including training for Tibetan fighters, logistical assistance through camps based in Nepal, and the organization of several aerial supply missions.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Earlier in 1956, armed conflict between Tibetan guerrillas and the PLA started in the Kham and Amdo regions, which had been subjected to socialist reform.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Guerrilla warfare later spread to other areas of Tibet and lasted through 1962.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Some regard the Xunhua Incident in 1958 as a precursor of the Tibetan uprising.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] The 10 March anniversary of the uprising is observed by exiled Tibetans as Tibetan Uprising Day and Women's Uprising Day.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] On 19 January 2009, the PRC-controlled legislature in the Tibet Autonomous Region chose 28 March as the national anniversary of Serfs Emancipation Day.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Smith Jr. describes the move as a "counter-propaganda" celebration following the 10 March 2008 unrest in Tibet.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] In 1951, the Seventeen Point Agreement between the People's Republic of China (PRC) and representatives of the Dalai Lama was put into effect.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Socialist reforms such as redistribution of land were delayed in Tibet proper.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] However, eastern Kham and Amdo (western Sichuan / Xikang and Qinghai provinces in the Chinese administrative hierarchy) were outside the administration of the Tibetan government in Lhasa, and were thus treated more like other Chinese provinces, with land redistribution implemented in full.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Khampas and nomads of Amdo traditionally owned their own land.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Armed resistance broke out in Amdo and eastern Kham in June 1956.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Prior to the PLA invasion, relations between Lhasa and the Khampa chieftains had deteriorated, although the Khampa remained spiritually loyal to the Dalai Lama throughout.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Because of these strained relations, the Khampa had actually assisted the Chinese communists in their initial invasion, before becoming the guerrilla resistance they are now known for.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Pandatsang Rapga, a pro-Kuomintang and pro-Republic of China Khampa revolutionary leader, offered the governor of Chamdo, Ngabo Ngawang Jigme, some Khampa fighters in exchange for the Tibetan government recognizing the independence of Kham.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] After the defeat of the Tibetan Army in Chamdo, Rapga started mediating in negotiations between the PRC and the Tibetan rebels.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Rapga and Topgay engaged in negotiations with the Chinese during their assault on Chamdo.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Khampas either defected to the Chinese PLA forces or did not fight at all.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Resistance fighters' attacks and People's Liberation Army reprisals against Khampa resistance groups such as the Chushi Gangdruk became increasingly brutal.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Kham's monastic networks came to be used by guerrilla forces to relay messages and hide rebels.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Punitive strikes were carried out by the Chinese government against Tibetan villages and monasteries.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Tibetan exiles assert that threats to bomb the Potala Palace and the Dalai Lama were bluffs made by Chinese military commanders in an attempt to intimidate the guerrilla forces into submission.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Lhasa continued to abide by the seventeen-point agreement and sent a delegation to Kham to quell the rebellion.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] After speaking with the rebel leaders, the delegation instead joined the rebellion.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Kham leaders contacted the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA), but the CIA under President Dwight D.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Eisenhower insisted it required an official request from Lhasa to support the rebels.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Eventually the CIA began to provide covert support for the rebellion without word from Lhasa.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] By then the rebellion had spread to Lhasa which had filled with refugees from Amdo and Kham.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Opposition to the Chinese presence in Tibet grew within the city of Lhasa.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] The next day, the Chinese leader saw a report from the PLA General Staff's Operations Department describing rebellions by Tibetans in Sichuan, Yunnan, Gansu, and Qinghai.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] He again stressed that "rebellions like these are extremely favorable for us because they will benefit us in helping to train our troops, train the people, and provide a sufficient reason to crush the rebellion and carry out comprehensive reforms in the future".
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] The PLA used Hui soldiers, who formerly had served under Ma Bufang to crush the Tibetan revolt in Amdo.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Hui cavalry were stationed in Southern Kham.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] The situation in all of Tibet became increasingly tense, as a growing number of Tibetans began to support the Khampa uprising, while "anti-Chinese communist agitation" spread among the Tibetans.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] The regional government in Lhasa neither wanted to back a rebellion nor publicly oppose it.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Dissatisfied, the Chinese Communist Party put pressure on the Dalai Lama's government to join the operations against the rebels, and made it increasingly clear that a spread of the insurgency would lead to "all-out repression" in Tibet.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] In this unstable situation, the Chinese generals resident in Lhasa was summoned back to mainland China, leaving the inexperienced PLA commander Tan Guansan in charge, just as the date of the Monlam Prayer Festival approached.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] This festival had previously been used by participants to voice "anti-Chinese sentiments".
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] According to historian Tsering Shakya, the Chinese government was pressuring the Dalai Lama to attend the National People's Congress in April 1959, in order to repair China's image in relation to ethnic minorities after the Khampa rebellion.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] According to the Dalai Lama's memoirs, the invitation came from Chinese General Zhang Jingwu, who proposed that the performance be held at the Chinese military headquarters; the Dalai Lama claimed that he had agreed.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] However, Tibetologist Sam van Schaik stated that the Dalai Lama was the one who proposed that the dance should take place in the military headquarters as the Norbulingka was too small.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Both parties did not yet agree on a date, and the Dalai Lama seemed to put the event "out of his mind", focusing instead on his ongoing examinations for his Geshe degree as well as the Monlam Prayer Festival.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Besides Tan and the Dalai Lama, nobody was seemingly informed of the plans for the dance.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] As a result, the date for the planned performance was only finalized 5 or 3 days beforehand when Tan reminded the Dalai Lama of the dance; the latter then suggested 10 March.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] The decision was seemingly concluded on a whim.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Neither the Kashag nor the Dalai Lama's bodyguards were informed of the Dalai Lama's plans until Chinese officials briefed them on 9 March, one day before the performance was scheduled, and insisted that they would handle the Dalai Lama's security.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Some members of the Kashag were alarmed and concerned that the Dalai Lama might be abducted, recalling a prophecy that told that the Dalai Lama should not exit his palace.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] According to historian Tsering Shakya, some Tibetan government officials feared that plans were being laid for a Chinese abduction of the Dalai Lama, and spread word to that effect amongst the inhabitants of Lhasa.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] On 10 March, several thousand Tibetans surrounded the Dalai Lama's palace to prevent him from leaving or being removed.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] The huge crowd had gathered in response to a rumor that the Chinese were planning to arrest the Dalai Lama when he went to a cultural performance at the PLA's headquarters.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] This marked the beginning of the uprising in Lhasa, though Chinese forces had skirmished with guerrillas outside the city in December of the previous year.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] The protesters publicly pleaded that the Dalai Lama should not attend the meeting with the Chinese officials, claiming that he would be kidnapped.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Although CCP officials insisted that the "reactionary upper stratum" in Lhasa was responsible for the rumor, there is no way to identify the precise source.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] At first, the violence was directed at Tibetan officials perceived not to have protected the Dalai Lama or to be pro-Chinese; attacks on Chinese started later.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] One of the first casualties of the mob was a senior lama, Pagbalha Soinam Gyamco, who worked with the PRC as a member of the Preparatory Committee of the Tibet Autonomous Region, who was killed and his body dragged by a horse in front of the crowd for 2 kilometres (1.2 mi).
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] The protesters also began to use openly anti-Chinese slogans such as "The Chinese must go, leave Tibet to Tibetans".
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] As protests and violence spread, the Dalai Lama informed the protesters that he would stay at the palace, yet this was no longer enough for the growing crowd.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Protesters began to demand Tibetan independence, and urged the Dalai Lama's government to publicly endorse their actions.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Barricades went up on the streets of Lhasa, and Chinese government soldiers and Tibetan rebel forces began to fortify positions within and around Lhasa in preparation for conflict.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] A petition of support for the armed rebels outside the city was taken up, and an appeal for assistance was made to the Indian consul.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Chinese and Tibetan troops continued moving into position over the next several days, with Chinese artillery pieces being deployed within range of the Dalai Lama's summer palace, the Norbulingka.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] On 12 March thousands of women gathered in front of the Potala Palace in Lhasa on the ground called Dri-bu-Yul-Khai Thang.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] The leader of this nonviolent demonstration was Pamo Kusang.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] This demonstration, now known as Women's Uprising Day, started the Tibetan women's movement for independence.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] After consulting the state oracle and concluding that the situation had become too unstable, the Dalai Lama and his close confidants opted to flee Lhasa.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] On 15 March, preparations for the Dalai Lama's evacuation from the city were set in motion, with Tibetan troops being employed to secure an escape route from Lhasa.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] On 17 March, two artillery shells landed near the Dalai Lama's palace, triggering his flight into exile.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Dalai Lama secretly left the palace the following night and slipped out of Lhasa with his family and a small number of officials.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Chinese had not strongly guarded the Potala, as they did not believe it likely that the Dalai Lama would try to flee.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] After reaching Lhoka, the Dalai Lama linked up with Kham rebels who began protecting him and upon reaching Lhotse at the Indian border, he proclaimed the restoration of Tibet's independence.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Rumours about the Dalai Lama's disappearance began to spread rapidly on the next day, though most still believed that he was in the palace.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Meanwhile, the situation in the city became increasingly tense, as protesters had seized a number of machine guns.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] At this point, remnants of the Tibetan Army had joined the protesters' ranks.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] On 20 March, the Chinese army responded by shelling the Norbulingka to disperse the crowd, and placed its troops at a barricade that divided the city into a northern and southern part in the following night.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] The battle began early on the following day and proved to be "bloody".
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Fighting in the streets continued for the next three days.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] The last Tibetan resistance was centered on the Jokhang, where Khampa refugees had set up machine guns, while a large number of Tibetans circumambulated the temple in reverence.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] The PLA started to attack the Jokhang on 23 March, and a hard-fought, three hours-long battle with many casualties on both sides ensued.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Chinese eventually managed to break through using a tank, whereupon they raised the flag of China on the temple, ending the uprising.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Lhasa's streets were reportedly littered with corpses, and at least 4,000 people were arrested.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Two British writers, Stuart and Roma Gelder, visited the Chensel Phodrang palace in the Norbulingka in 1962 and "found its contents meticulously preserved".
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Indian government under Nehru expressed concerns of the Tibetan people and condemned China as an aggressive power due to the violent suppression of the revolt by the PLA.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Pandatsang Rapga, a pro-Kuomintang and pro-Republic of China revolutionary Khampa leader, was instrumental in the revolt against the communists.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Kuomintang had a history of using Khampa fighters to oppose both the Dalai Lama's Tibetan government, and battle the Chinese Red Army.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Rapga continued to cooperate with the ROC government after it fled to Taiwan.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] The ROC government disagreed with the US government on whether Tibet should be independent, since the ROC claimed Tibet as part of its territory.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Rapga agreed to a plan in which the revolt against the communists would include anti feudalism, land reform, a modern government, and to give power to the people.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] However, the Dalai Lama's first visit to Taiwan in 1997 was said to have somewhat improved the two communities' general relationship, although "tension" allegedly still exists between them due to considerable differences.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Dalai Lama's visit also allowed for Tibetans to visit Taiwan without directly contacting the Mongolian and Tibetan Affairs Commission, and some Tibetans in Taiwan (such as Changa Tsering, an incumbent MTAC committee member) subsequently attended the celebration of the Dalai Lama's visit in 1997.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Tibetan community in Taiwan was also formerly divided between loyalty to the Dalai Lama and Taiwan's MTAC, although the MTAC was formally dissolved in 2017.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] The employees and responsibilities of the commission were thus officially reassigned to two places: the Mongolian and Tibetan Cultural Center under the Ministry of Culture, and the expanded Department of Hong Kong, Macao, Inner Mongolia, and Tibet Affairs under the Mainland Affairs Council.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Tibetologist Tom Grunfeld said "the veracity of such a claim is difficult to verify".
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Smith, a writer with Radio Free Asia, writes that the "secret documents" came from a 1960 PLA report captured by guerrillas in 1966, with the figures first published by the TGIE in India in 1990.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Smith states that the documents said that 87,000 "enemies were eliminated", but he does not take "eliminated" to mean "killed", as the TGIE does.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Peace Research Institute Oslo (PRIO) estimated 10,000 Tibetan and 2,000 PLA battle deaths.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Lhasa had a population of sixty to seventy thousand at the time.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Estimates covering 1956–59 including areas outside Lhasa put civilian deaths at around 60,000 and military deaths at around 40,000.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Following the uprising, the Chinese government launched a wide-reaching campaign to consolidate control and implement socialist reforms across Tibet.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Lhasa's three major monasteries - Sera, Ganden, and Drepung were heavily damaged by shelling, with Sera and Drepung reportedly left nearly beyond repair.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] According to the TGIE, members of the Dalai Lama's bodyguard who were remaining in Lhasa were disarmed and publicly executed, along with Tibetans who were found to be harbouring weapons in their homes.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Thousands of Tibetan monks were executed or arrested, and monasteries and temples around the city were looted or destroyed.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] After the 12 March Women's Uprising demonstration, many of the women who were involved in it were imprisoned, including the leader of the demonstration, Pamo Kusang.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] "Some of them were tortured, died in prison, or were executed." Known as Women's Uprising Day, this demonstration started the Tibetan women's movement for independence.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Meanwhile, the CIA continued to support Tibetan resistance from 1957 to 1972, training agents in the United States and inserting them into Tibet to organize rebellions against the People's Liberation Army (PLA).
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] CIA officer Bruce Walker, who oversaw the program, later expressed concern about the hostility that the radio teams encountered from the local population inside Tibet, with at least one group reportedly betrayed by his own brother, and all three agents were arrested.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Despite the arrests, those agents were not mistreated and were later released across the Indian border after undergoing less than a month of propaganda sessions.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] In April 1959, the 19-year-old Panchen Lama, the second ranking spiritual leader in Tibet, residing in Shigatse, called on Tibetans to support the Chinese government.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] However, after a tour through Tibet in May 1962, he wrote a document which is known as the 70,000 Character Petition.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] The document was addressed to Zhou Enlai and in it, he criticized Chinese abuses in Tibet.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Shortly afterward, he met with Zhou in order to have a discussion about the document.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] The outlined petition dealt with the brutal suppression of the Tibetan people both during and after the PLA's invasion of Tibet and the sufferings of the people in The Great Leap Forward.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] In this document, he criticized the suppression that the Chinese authorities had conducted in retaliation for the 1959 Tibetan uprising.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] But in October 1962, the PRC authorities who were dealing with the population criticized the petition.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Chairman Mao called the petition "... a poisoned arrow shot at the Party by reactionary feudal overlords." In 1967, the Panchen Lama was formally arrested and imprisoned until his release in 1977.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] In June 1959, the Buddhist monk Palden Gyatso was arrested for demonstrating during the March uprising by Chinese officials.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] He spent the next 33 years in Chinese prisons and laogai or "reform through labor" camps, the longest term of any Tibetan political prisoner.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] He was tortured, including with a cattle prod that was activated in his mouth and which led to the loss of his teeth.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] As part of the occupation of Tibet, in July 1959, the PLA occupied several Bhutanese enclaves in western Tibet which were under Bhutanese administration for more than 300 years, having been ceded to Bhutan by Ngawang Namgyal in the 17th century.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] These included Darchen, Labrang Monastery, Gartok and several smaller monasteries and villages near Mount Kailas.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Chinese authorities have interpreted the uprising as a revolt by the Tibetan elite against socialist reforms that were improving the lives of Tibetan serfs.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Tibetan exile sources and some independent sources, on the other hand, have usually interpreted it as a popular uprising against Chinese rule.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Historian Tsering Shakya has argued that the revolt reflected widespread dissatisfaction both with the Chinese authorities and also with the Tibetan government in Lhasa, which was seen as unable to protect the Dalai Lama's authority and Tibetan sovereignty.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Dalai Lama, fearing for his safety, fled Lhasa on March 17, 1959, and eventually found refuge in India.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] Upon reaching India, he and his followers were granted asylum by the Indian government, marking the beginning of his exile.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] From his residence in Dharamshala, Himachal Pradesh, the Dalai Lama played a major role in promoting Tibetan Buddhism internationally and raising awareness of the Tibetan cause.
[src:ashoka/1959-tibetan-uprising] According to Chope Paljor Tsering, a former minister in the Central Tibetan Administration, “Buddhism has not only survived, but been revived and appreciated... by many cultures around the world,” suggesting that the Dalai Lama has helped reshape global perceptions of Buddhism.
[src:ashoka/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] The **3rd Karmapa, Rangjung Dorje** (Tibetan: རང་འབྱུང་རྡོ་རྗེ་, Wylie: rang 'byung rdo rje) (1284–1339) was the 3rd Gyalwa Karmapa and head of the Karma Kagyu school, the largest school within the Kagyu tradition.
[src:ashoka/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] He was an important figure in the history of Tibetan Buddhism, who helped to spread Buddha-nature teachings in Tibet.
[src:ashoka/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Rangjung Dorjé was officially recognized as the first tulku, the reincarnation of Karma Pakshi, in 1282.
[src:ashoka/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] The 3rd Karmapa was raised at the Tsurphu Monastery, where he received teachings from both the Kagyu and Nyingma traditions from eminent masters such as Trophu Künden Sherab and Nyenre Gendün Bum.
[src:ashoka/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] He became renowned as one of the greatest masters of his time and had a large number of disciples.
[src:ashoka/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] He undertook a spiritual retreat on the slopes of Everest, received full ordination, and completed his studies at a significant Kadampa teaching center.
[src:ashoka/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Rangjung Dorje visited China, where the emperor Toghon Temur became his disciple.
[src:ashoka/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Upon his death, Rangjung Dorje's face is said to have appeared in the moon there.
[src:ashoka/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] As a tulku lineage, the Karmapas were among the earliest recognized Tulkus, reincarnated as deities.
[src:ashoka/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] The first Karmapas were influential in the Mongolian Yuan and Chinese Ming courts as well as the Tangut Western Xia Kingdom.
[src:ashoka/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Through visions, he is believed to have received teachings on the "Wheel of Time", the Kalachakra.
[src:ashoka/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] In 1284 he authored an astrological compendium entitled *The Compendium of Astrology* (Tib.
[src:ashoka/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] *rtsis kun bsdus pa*), from which a Tibetan calendar was developed by the lineage of the Gyalwang Karmapas.
[src:ashoka/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Called the Tsurphu tradition calendar or the Tsurluk calendar, his astrological compendium was the basis from which many treatises authored by the subsequent Karmapas and by Jamgon Kongtrul the Great evolved.
[src:ashoka/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] The Tsurluk calendar is still used by the Karma Kagyu and overseen by Tsipa Gelek Dhargay, at the 17th Karmapa, Ogyen Trinley Dorje's seat in Rumtek, Sikkim, India.
[src:ashoka/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Rangjung Dorje was also known as a great practitioner of Traditional Tibetan medicine.
[src:ashoka/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Born to a Nyingma family, Rangjung Dorje was a lineage-holder in both the Karma Kagyu and the Nyingma tradition of Dzogchen.
[src:ashoka/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] He was a disciple of the Nyingma master Rigdzin Kumaradza Shönnu Gyelpo (Tibetan: rig 'dzin ku ma ra dza gzhon nu rgyal po; 1266–1343) who passed on to him the "heart-essence" (nying-thig) teachings transmitted by Padmasambhava and Vimalamitra (the Khandro Nyingtik and Vima Nyingtik respectively).
[src:ashoka/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] He also encountered the Nyingma master Longchenpa, who transmitted to him certain Dzogchen teachings.
[src:ashoka/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] In exchange, Rangjung Dorje imparted important "New Translation" Tantras to Longchenpa.
[src:ashoka/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Rangjung Dorje was also a "Treasure revealer" of termas.
[src:ashoka/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] The Karma Kagyu Dzogchen transmission that arose from his lineage is known as the "Karma-Nyingthig" (Tibetan: kar ma snying thig; Essence of the Heart of the Karma School).
[src:ashoka/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] In 1321 the famous scholar Dolpopa (1292–1361) visited Tsurphu Monastery for the first time and had extensive discussions with Rangjung Dorje about doctrinal issues.
[src:ashoka/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] It appears that Rangjung Dorje almost certainly influenced the development of some of Dolpopa's theories, possibly including his Zhentong (*gzhan stong*) method.
[src:ashoka/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] According to Karma phrin las, *Dri lan yid*, 91-92, his teacher, Chödrak Gyatso, the Seventh Karmapa, interpreted the nature of Zhentong (*gzhan stong*) accepted by Rangjung Dorje.
[src:ashoka/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] 15) conveys that the Third Karmapa was a systematizer of the Chöd developed by Machig Labdrön and lists a number of his works on Chod consisting of redactions, outlines and commentaries.
[src:ashoka/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Yungtön Dorjepel (1284–1365), (the previous incarnation of the First Panchen Lama, Khedrup Je), studied the Great Perfection due to the great inspiration of Rangjung Dorje.
[src:ashoka/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Rangjung Dorje was a noted scholar who composed many significant texts, the most famous of which is the *Profound Inner Meaning* (Wylie: *zab mo nang don*), which concern the Vajrayana inner yoga practices.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] The **969 Movement** (Burmese: ၉၆၉ လှုပ်ရှားမှု) is a Buddhist nationalist organisation opposed to the perceived expansion of Islam in predominantly Buddhist Myanmar.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] The three digits of 969 "symbolise the virtues of the Buddha, Buddhist practices and the Buddhist community".
[src:ashoka/969-movement] The first 9 represents the nine special attributes of the Buddha in Buddhism, the 6 represents the six special attributes of his teachings (the Dharma), and the second 9 represents the nine special attributes of the Sangha (the Buddhist monastic community).
[src:ashoka/969-movement] Those special attributes are the Three Jewels of the Buddha.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] In the past, the Buddha, Sangha, Dharma, the wheel of Dharma, and "969" were Buddhist signs.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] The movement has had strong reactions within and beyond Myanmar.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] It has received criticism in international media.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] In April 2013, *The Straits Times* reported that critics remained sceptical after Wirathu, the movement's leader, responded to recent anti-Muslim violence with pledges to work for peace.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] Various media organizations have described the movement as being anti-Muslim or "Islamophobic".
[src:ashoka/969-movement] The movement's Myanmar Buddhist supporters deny it is anti-Muslim, with Wirathu stating it is a protective movement about targeting "Bengalis who are terrorizing ethnic Rakhine (Buddhists)".
[src:ashoka/969-movement] Alex Bookbinder, in *The Atlantic*, links the movement's origins in a book written in the late 1990s by Kyaw Lwin, a functionary in the Ministry of Religious Affairs, and its precepts are rooted in a traditional belief in numerology.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] Across South Asia, Muslims represent the phrase "In the Name of God, the Compassionate and Merciful" with the number 786, and businesses display the number to indicate that they are Muslim-owned.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] 969 proponents see this as a Muslim plot to conquer Burma in the 21st century, based on the premise that 7 plus 8 plus 6 is equal to 21.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] The number 969 is intended to be 786's cosmological opposite.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] Wirathu is regarded as the movement's highest protector.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] It has been reported that he advocates the boycott of shops owned by Muslims.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] Wirathu has himself stated that the movement has been treated as a scapegoat by being unfairly blamed for events like the 2012 Rakhine State riots, and maintains that "969 is not violent".
[src:ashoka/969-movement] The *Asia Times Online* has described him as a "complex figure" who demonises Muslims, but also protests police violence.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] An article in *The Straits Times* says a source indicated that Wirathu had changed his tone and "pledged to promote peace among religious communities".
[src:ashoka/969-movement] The cover story of the 20 June 2013 issue of *Time* magazine called Wirathu "The Face of Buddhist Terror".
[src:ashoka/969-movement] "You can be full of kindness and love, but you cannot sleep next to a mad dog", Wirathu said, referring to Muslims.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] "If we are weak", he said, "our land will become Muslim".
[src:ashoka/969-movement] "Some people misunderstood the title [of the *Time* article] ... seeing it as an insult to religion", said Dr.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] "They believe it’s equating Buddhism with terrorism".
[src:ashoka/969-movement] After the publication of the *Time* article, Wirathu denied responsibility for anti-Muslim violence.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] Shortly after, the June 2013 issue of *Time* featuring Wirathu was banned in Myanmar.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] Burma's government has objected to the magazine article.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] Authorities deny they are defending the monk, Wirathu, but said they were concerned the article could create problems after recent unrest between Buddhists and Muslims.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] Burmese President Thein Sein, however, has defended Wirathu, saying the monk's order was striving for peace and prosperity and that the report undermined efforts to rebuild trust between faiths.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] "The government is currently striving with religious leaders, political parties, media and the people to rid Myanmar [Burma] of unwanted conflicts," he added.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] Wirathu has said that the *Time* article was not against Buddhism, just against him.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] In an interview with *The Irrawaddy* magazine, he also alleged Muslim extremists were behind the article and planning to wage jihad against Burma.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] Hundreds of protesters took to the streets of Yangon early in the afternoon on 30 June 2013 in a peaceful demonstration against *Time* magazine's article on Wirathu and the 969 movement.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] Marching monks held a banner proclaiming that Wirathu is "not a terrorist, but a protector of race, language and religion".
[src:ashoka/969-movement] Speaking to Mizzima News, one demonstrator, a 51-year-old office manager, said, "Time magazine is wrong.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] In September 2014, Wirathu attended a "Great Sangha Conference" in Colombo organised by Bodu Bala Sena.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] Wirathu said that his 969 Movement would work with the Bodu Bala Sena.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] The movement is seeking to draft a law that would forbid Buddhist women from marrying non-Buddhist men without the permission of local officials.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] Dhammapiya, a senior monk who helped write the original proposal for the laws, said they were meant to encourage peace between different faiths and to "protect" Buddhist women from being forced to convert to Islam when they married Muslim men.
[src:ashoka/969-movement] Government religious regulatory authorities, while supporting the protection of the Buddhist faith from perceived Islamic threats, reject the legal initiatives of the 969 movement and "prohibited the creation of formal organisations" based on 969 principles.
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] In architecture, an **abacus** (from the Ancient Greek ἄβαξ (*ábax*), 'slab'; or French *abaque*, *tailloir*; pl.: **abacuses** or **abaci**) is a flat slab forming the uppermost member or division of the capital of a column, above the bell.
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] Its chief function is to provide a large supporting surface, tending to be wider than the capital, as an abutment to receive the weight of the arch or the architrave above.
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] The diminutive of abacus, **abaculus**, is used to describe small mosaic tiles, also called **abaciscus** or **tessera**, used to create ornamental floors with detailed patterns of chequers or squares in a tessellated pavement.
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] In classical architecture, the shape of the abacus and its edge profile varies in the different classical orders.
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] In the Greek Doric order, the abacus is a plain square slab without mouldings, supported on an echinus.
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] In the Roman and Renaissance Doric orders, it is crowned by a moulding (known as "crown moulding").
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] In the Tuscan and Roman Doric capital, it may rest on a boltel.
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] In the archaic Greek Ionic order, owing to the greater width of the capital, the abacus is rectangular in plan, and consists of a carved ovolo moulding.
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] In later examples, the slab is thinner and the abacus remains square, except where there are angled volutes, where the slab is slightly curved.
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] In the Roman and Renaissance Ionic capital, the abacus is square with a fillet on the top of an ogee moulding with curved edges over angled volutes.
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] In an angular capital of the Greek Corinthian order, the abacus is moulded, its sides are concave, and its angles canted (except in one or two exceptional Greek capitals, where it is brought to a sharp angle); the volutes of adjacent faces meet and project diagonally under each corner of the abacus.
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] The same shape is adopted in the Roman and Renaissance Corinthian and Composite capitals, in some cases with the carved ovolo moulding, fillet, and cavetto.
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] In Romanesque architecture, the abacus survives as a heavier slab, generally moulded and decorated.
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] In Gothic architecture, the moulded forms of the abacus vary in shape, such as square, circular, or even octagonal, it may even be a flat disk or drum.
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] The form of the Gothic abacus is often affected by the shape of a vault that springs from the column, in which case it is called an impost block.
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] In *śilpaśāstra*, the ancient Indian science of sculpture, the abacus is commonly termed as *phalaka* (or *phalakā*).
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] It consists of a flat plate and forms part of the standard pillar (stambha).
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] The *phalaka* should be constructed below the *potikā* ("bracket").
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] It is commonly found together with the dish-like maṇḍi as a single unit.
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] The term is found in encyclopedic books such as the *Mānasāra*, *Kāmikgāgama* and the *Suprabhedāgama*.
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] Early Saxon abaci are frequently simply chamfered, but sometimes grooved as in the crypt at Repton (fig.
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] 1) and in the arcade of the refectory at Westminster Abbey.
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] The abacus in Norman work is square where the columns are small; but on larger piers it is sometimes octagonal, as at Waltham Abbey.
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] The square of the abacus is often sculptured with ornaments, as at the White Tower and at Alton, Hampshire (fig.
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] In Early English work, the abacus is generally circular, and in larger work, a group of circles (fig.
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] 4), with some examples of octagonal and square shapes.
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] The mouldings are generally half-rounds, which overhang deep hollows in the capital.
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] In France, the abacus in early work is generally square, as at Chateau de Blois (fig.
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] 5) is decorated with simple mouldings and ornaments, common during the 12th century, in Île-de-France, Normandy, Champagne, and Burgundy regions, and from the choir of Vézelay Abbey (fig.
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] Figure 7 shows a circular abacus used at windows in the side chapels of Notre Dame de Paris.
[src:ashoka/abacus-architecture] Towards the end of the 13th century, this element decreases in importance—they became short with a narrow profile during the 14th century, and disappeared almost entirely during the 15th century (fig.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] Tagore sought to modernise Mughal and Rajput styles to counter the influence of Western models of art, as taught in art schools under the British Raj.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] Along with other artists from the Bengal school of art, Tagore advocated in favour of a nationalistic Indian art derived from Indian art history, drawing inspiration from the Ajanta Caves.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] Tagore's work was so successful that it was eventually accepted and promoted as a national Indian style within British art institutions.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] Abanindranath Tagore was born in Jorasanko, Calcutta, British India, to Gunendranath Tagore and Saudamini Devi.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] His grandfather was Girindranath Tagore, the second son of "Prince" Dwarkanath Tagore.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] He was a member of the distinguished Tagore family and a nephew of the poet Rabindranath Tagore.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] His grandfather and his elder brother, Gaganendranath Tagore, were also artists.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] Tagore learned art while studying at Sanskrit College, Kolkata in the 1880s.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] In 1890, Tagore attended the Calcutta School of Art where he learnt to use pastels from O.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] Palmer, European painters who taught in that institution.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] In 1888, he married Suhasini Devi, daughter of Bhujagendra Bhusan Chatterjee, a descendant of Prasanna Coomar Tagore.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] He left Sanskrit College after nine years of study and studied English as a special student at St.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] Xavier's College, which he attended for about a year and a half.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] He had a sister, Sunayani Devi, who was also a painter.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] Her paintings depicted both mythological and domestic scenes, some of which were inspired by Patachitra.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] In the early 1890s several of his illustrations were published in *Sadhana* magazine, and in Chitrangada, and other works by Rabindranath Tagore.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] Around 1897 he took lessons from the vice-principal of the Government School of Art, studying in the traditional European academic manner, learning the full range of techniques, but with a particular interest in watercolour.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] It was during this period that he developed his interest in Mughal art, producing a number of works based on the life of Krishna in a Mughal-influenced style.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] Havell, Tagore worked with him to revitalise and redefine teaching of art at the Calcutta School of Art, a project also supported by his brother Gaganendranath, who set up the Indian Society of Oriental Art.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] Tagore believed in the traditional Indian techniques of painting.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] His philosophy rejected the "materialistic" art of the West and came back to Indian traditional art forms.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] He was influenced by the Mughal school of painting as well as Whistler's Aestheticism.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] In his later works, Tagore started integrating Chinese and Japanese calligraphic traditions into his style.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] He believed that Western art was "materialistic" in character, and that India needed to return to its own traditions to recover its spiritual values.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] Despite its Indo-centric nationalism, this view was already commonplace within British art of the time, stemming from the ideas of the Pre-Raphaelites.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] Tagore's work also shows the influence of Whistler's Aestheticism.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] Partly for this reason many British arts administrators were sympathetic to such ideas, especially as Hindu philosophy was becoming increasingly influential in the West following the spread of the Theosophy movement.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] Tagore believed that Indian traditions could be adapted to express these new values, and to promote a progressive Indian national culture.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] His finest achievement was the Arabian Nights series which was painted in 1930.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] In these paintings he uses the Arabian Nights stories as a means of looking at colonial Calcutta and picturing its emergent cosmopolitanism.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] With the success of Tagore's ideas, he came into contact with other Asian cultural figures, such as the Japanese art historian Okakura Kakuzō and the Japanese painter Yokoyama Taikan, whose work was comparable to his own.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] In his later work, he began to incorporate elements of Chinese and Japanese calligraphic traditions into his art, seeking to construct a model for a modern pan-Asian artistic tradition which would merge the common aspects of Eastern spiritual and artistic cultures.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] His close students included Nandalal Bose, Samarendranath Gupta, Kshitindranath Majumdar, Surendranath Ganguly, Asit Kumar Haldar, Sarada Ukil, Kalipada Ghoshal, Manishi Dey, Mukul Dey, K.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] For Tagore, the house he grew up in (5 Dwarakanath Tagore Lane) and its companion house (6 Dwarakanath Tagore Lane) connected two cultural worlds – 'white town' (where the British colonisers lived) and 'black town' (where the natives lived).
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] According to architectural historian Swati Chattopadhay, Tagore used the Bengali meaning of the word, Jorasanko ('double bridge') to develop this idea in the form of a mythical map of the city.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] The map was, indeed, not of Calcutta, but an imaginary city, Halisahar, and was the central guide in a children's story Putur Boi (Putu's Book).
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] The nineteenth-century place names of Calcutta, however, appear on this map, thus suggesting that this imaginary city be read with the colonial city as a frame of reference.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] Tagore maintained throughout his life a long friendship with the London-based artist, author and eventual president of London's Royal College of Art, William Rothenstein.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] Arriving in the autumn of 1910, Rothenstein spent almost a year surveying India's cultural and religious sites, including the ancient Buddhist caves of Ajanta; the Jain carvings of Gwalior; and the Hindu panoply of Benares.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] He ended up in Calcutta, where he drew and painted with Tagore and his students, attempting to absorb elements of Bengal School style into his own practice.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] However limited Rothenstein's experiments with the styles of early Modernist Indian painting were, the friendship between him and Abanindranath Tagore ushered in a crucial cultural event.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] This was Rabindranath Tagore's time living at Rothenstein's London home, which led to the publication of the English-language version of Gitanjali and the subsequent award to Rabindranath in 1913 of the Nobel Prize for Literature.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] The publication of Rabindranath Tagore's Gitanjali in English brought the Tagore family international renown, which helped to make Abanindranath Tagore's artistic projects better known in the West.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] Abanindranath Tagore became chancellor of Visva Bharati in 1942.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] Within a few years of the artist's death in 1951, his eldest son, Alokendranath, bequeathed almost the entire family collection of Abanindranath Tagore's paintings to the newly founded Rabindra Bharati Society Trust that took up residence on the site of their famous house on No.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] As only a small number of the artist's paintings had been collected or given away in his lifetime, the Rabindra Bharati Society became the main repository of Tagore's works throughout his life.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] Banished into trunks inside the dark offices of the society, these paintings have remained in permanent storage ever since.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] As a result, the full range and brilliance of Tagore's works has never be effectively projected into the public domain.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] They remained intimately known only to a tiny circle of art connoisseurs and scholars in Bengal, some of whom like K.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] Siva Kumar have long argued that the true measure of Tagore's talent is to be found in his works of the 1920s, 1930s and 1940s but could do little to offer up a comprehensive profile of the master for the contemporary art world.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] Siva Kumar's Paintings of Abanindranath Tagore (2008) is a path-breaking book redefining Tagore's art.
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] Another book that constitutes a serious reconsideration of Tagore's art, contextualising it as a critique of modernity and the nation-state is Debashish Banerji's The Alternate Nation of Abanindranath Tagore (2010).
[src:ashoka/abanindranath-tagore] Indian film director Purnendu Pattrea made a documentary film on the artist, titled *Abanindranath*, in 1976.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] "about the dharma") refers to a class of Buddhist texts, the first of which date from the 3rd century BCE.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Abhidharma texts contain detailed scholastic presentations of Buddhist doctrine, including doctrines that appear in canonical Buddhist scriptures and commentaries.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] "Abhidharma" also refers to the scholastic method itself, and the knowledge (prajña) that this method is said to study and cultivate.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] There are different types of Abhidharma literature.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The early canonical Abhidharma works, such as the Pali *Abhidhamma Piṭaka*, are not philosophical treatises but mainly summaries and expositions of early Buddhist doctrinal lists with their accompanying explanations.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] These texts developed out of early Buddhist lists or matrices (*mātṛkās*) of key teachings.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Later post-canonical Abhidharma works were written as either large treatises (*śāstra*), as commentaries (*aṭṭhakathā*), or as smaller introductory manuals.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] There were numerous schools of Abhidharma in India, such as the Theravada, and the Vaibhāṣika.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] They are more developed philosophical works which include many innovations and doctrines not found in the canonical Abhidharma.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Abhidharma remains an important field of scholarship among the Theravāda, Mahāyāna, and Vajrayāna schools of Buddhism.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] They held that Abhidharma was taught by the Buddha to his most eminent disciples, and that therefore this justified the inclusion of Abhidharma texts into their scriptural canon.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] According to Collett Cox, Abhidharma started as a systematic elaboration of the teachings of the Buddhist sūtras, but later developed independent doctrines.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Two interpretations of the term "Abhi-dharma" are common.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] According to Analayo, the initial meaning of Abhidharma in the earliest texts (such as the *Mahāgosiṅga-sutta* and its parallels) was simply a discussion concerning the Dharma, or talking about the Dharma.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] In this sense, *abhi* has the meaning of "about" or "concerning," and can also be seen in the parallel term *abhivinaya* (which just means discussions about the vinaya).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The other interpretation, where *abhi* is interpreted as meaning "higher" or "superior", and thus *Abhidharma* means "higher teaching", seems to have been a later development.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Some Western scholars have considered the Abhidharma to be the core of what is referred to as "Buddhism and psychology".
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Other scholars on the topic, such as Nyanaponika Thera and Dan Lusthaus, describe Abhidharma as a Buddhist phenomenology while Noa Ronkin and Kenneth Inada equate it with process philosophy.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Bhikkhu Bodhi writes that the system of the *Abhidhamma Piṭaka* is "simultaneously a philosophy, a psychology and an ethics, all integrated into the framework of a program for liberation." According to L.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Cousins, the Buddhist sūtras deal with sequences and processes, while the Abhidharma texts describe occasions and events.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Modern scholars generally believe that the canonical Abhidharma texts emerged after the time of Gautama Buddha, in around the 3rd century BCE.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Therefore, the canonical Abhidharma works are generally claimed by scholars not to represent the words of the Buddha himself, but those of later Buddhist thinkers.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Peter Skilling describes the Abhidharma literature as "the end-product of several centuries of intellectual endeavor".
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The Vinaya accounts on the compilation of the Buddhist Canon following the *parinirvāṇa* of Gautama Buddha (c.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] 5th century BCE) offer various and sometimes conflicting narratives regarding the canonical status of Abhidharma.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] According to Analayo, "the Mūlasarvāstivāda Vinaya does not explicitly mention the Abhidharma, although it reports that on this occasion Mahākāśyapa recited the mātṛkā(s)." Analayo thinks that this reflects an early stage, when what later became Abhidharma was called the *mātṛkās*.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The term appears in some sūtras, such as the *Mahāgopālaka-sutta* (and its Sanskrit parallel) which says that a learned monk is one who knows the Dharma, Vinaya, and the mātṛkās.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Western scholars of Buddhist studies such as André Migot, Edward J.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Thomas, Erich Frauwallner, Rupert Gethin, and Johannes Bronkhorst have argued that the Abhidharma was based on early and ancient lists of doctrinal terms which are called *mātikās* (Sanskrit: *mātṛkā*).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Migot points to the mention of a "*Mātṛkā Piṭaka"* in the *Cullavagga* as the precursor to the canonical *Abhidharma*.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Migot argues that this *Mātṛkā Piṭaka*, said to have been recited by Mahākāśyapa at the First Council according to the *Ashokavadana*, likely began as a condensed version of the Buddhist doctrine that was expanded over time.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Thomas and Frauwallner both argue that while the Abhidharma texts of the different schools were compiled separately and have major differences, they are based on an "ancient core" of common material.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Rupert Gethin also writes that the *mātikās* are from an earlier date than the Abhidharma texts themselves.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The extensive use of *mātṛkā* can be found in some early Buddhist texts, including the *Saṅgīti Sutta* and *Dasuttara Sutta* of the Dīgha Nikāya, as well as the *Saṅgīti Sūtra* and *Daśottara Sūtra* of the Dīrgha Āgama.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Similar lists of numerically arranged doctrinal terms can be found in AN 10.27 and AN 10.28.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Tse fu Kuan also argues that certain sūtras of the *Aṅguttara Nikāya* (AN 3.25, AN 4.87–90, AN 9.42–51) illustrates an Abhidharma method.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Another text which contains a similar list that acts as a doctrinal summary is the *Madhyama-āgama* ("Discourse on Explaining the Spheres", MĀ 86) which includes a list of thirty one topics to be taught to newly ordained monastics.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The last sutra of the *Madhyama-āgama* (MĀ 222) contains a similar doctrinal summary listing, which combines three lists into one: a list of eight activities, a list of ten mental qualities and practices, and the twelve links of dependent arising.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] These two do not have any parallels in Pali.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] According to Analayo, another important doctrinal list which appears in the early texts is the "thirty seven qualities that are conducive to awakening" (*bodhipākṣikā dharmāḥ*).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] This *mātṛkā* appears in various sūtras, like the *Pāsādika-sutta*, the *Sāmagāma-sutta* (and their parallels), and in the *Mahāparinirvāṇa-sūtra*, where it is said to have been taught by the Buddha just before passing away.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Analayo notes that these various lists served a useful purpose in early Buddhism since they served as aids for the memorization and teaching of the Buddhist doctrine.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The use of lists containing doctrinal statements can similarly be seen in Jain literature.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The fact that these lists were seen by the early Buddhists as a way to preserve and memorize the doctrine can be seen in the *Saṅgīti Sūtra* and its various parallels, which mention how the Jain community became divided over doctrinal matters after the death of their leader.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The sutta depicts Śāriputra as reciting a list of doctrinal terms and stating that the community will remain "united, unanimous, and in unison we will not dispute" regarding the teaching and also states they will recite together the doctrine.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The close connection between the *Saṅgīti Sūtra* and Abhidharma can be seen in the fact that it became the basis for one of the seven canonical Abhidharma texts belonging to the Sarvāstivāda school, the *Saṅgītiparyāya*, which is effectively a commentary on the sūtra.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Frauwallner notes that basic fundamental concepts such as the 12 *āyatanāni,* the 18 *dhatāvah*, and the 5 *skandhāh* often occur as a group in the early Buddhist texts.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] He also points out another such list that occurs in various texts "comprises several groups of elements of import for entanglement in the cycle of existence" and was modeled on the *Oghavagga* of the *Samyuttanikaya*.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Another related early method is called the *mātṛkā* ("attribute"), and refers to lists of terms divided by a dyad or triad of attributes.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] For example, terms could be grouped into those things that are *rūpa* (form, physical) or *arūpa* (formless), *saṃskṛtam* (constructed) or *asaṃskṛtam,* and the triad of *kuśalam* (wholesome), *akuśalam* (unwholesome), or *avyākṛtam* (indetermined).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] An early form of this method can be found in the *Dasuttara Sutta*.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The explanations of the various elements in these lists also dealt with how these elements were connected (*saṃprayoga*) with each other.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Over time, the need arose for an overarching way to classify all these terms and doctrinal elements, and the first such framework was to subsume or include (*saṃgraha*) all main terms into the schema of the 12 *āyatanāni,* the 18 *dhatāvah*, and the 5 *skandhāh*.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Over time, the initial scholastic method of listing and categorizing terms was expanded in order to provide a complete and comprehensive systematization of the Buddhist doctrine.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] According to Analayo, these various lists were also not presented alone, but included some kind of commentary and explanation which was also part of the oral tradition.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Sometimes this commentary included quotations from other sutras, and traces of this can be found in the canonical Abhidharma texts.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] As time passed, these commentaries and their accompanying lists became inseparable from each other, and the commentaries gained canonical status.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Therefore, the different Buddhist Abhidharma texts were developed over time as Buddhist monks and philosophers expanded their analytical methods in different ways.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Since this happened in different monastic communities located in different regions, they developed in separate doctrinal directions.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] This divergence was perhaps enhanced by the various schisms in the early Buddhist community and also by geographic distance.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] According to Frauwallner, the period of the development of the canonical Abhidharma texts is between 250 and 50 BCE.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] By the time, the different canons began to be written down, and as a result the Abhidharma texts of the early Buddhist schools were substantially different, as can be seen in how different the canonical Abhidharma texts are in the Sarvāstivādin and Theravādin schools.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] These differences are much more pronounced than among the other canonical collections (Sūtras, Āgama, and Vinaya).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] As such, the Abhidharma collections of the various Buddhist schools are much more unique to each sect.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The various Abhidharmic traditions grew to have very fundamental philosophical disagreements with each other (such as on the status of the person, or temporal eternalism).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Thus, according to Frauwallner, the different Abhidharma canons contained collections of doctrines which were sometimes unrelated to each other and sometimes contradictory.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] These different Abhidharmic theories were (together with differences in Vinaya) some of the various causes for the splits in the monastic Saṃgha, which resulted in the fragmented early Buddhist landscape of the early Buddhist schools.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] These various Abhidharma works were not accepted by all Indian Buddhist schools as canonical; for example, the Mahāsāṃghika school seems not to have accepted them as part of their Buddhist canon.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Another school included most of the *Khuddaka Nikāya* within the *Abhidhamma Piṭaka*.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] After the closing of the foundational Buddhist canons, Abhidharma texts continued to be composed, but now they were either commentaries on the canonical texts (like the Pāli *Aṭṭhakathās* and the *Mahāvibhāṣa*), or independent treatises (*śāstra*) in their own right.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] In these post-canonical texts, further doctrinal developments and innovations can be found.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Some of these texts surpassed the canonical Abhidharma in influence and popularity, becoming the orthodox summas of their particular schools' Abhidharma.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Two exegetical texts, both from the 5th century, stand above the rest as the most influential.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The works of Buddhaghosa (5th century CE), particularly the *Visuddhimagga*, remains the main reference work of the Theravāda school, while the *Abhidharmakośa* (4–5th century CE) of Vasubandhu remains the primary source for Abhidharma studies in both Indo-Tibetan Buddhism and East Asian Buddhism.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] In the modern era, only the Abhidharma texts of the Sarvāstivādins and the Theravādins have survived as complete collections, each consisting of seven books with accompanying commentarial literature.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] A small number of other Abhidharma texts are preserved in the Chinese Canon and also in Sanskrit fragments, such as the *Śāriputra Abhidharma Śāstra* of the Dharmaguptaka school and various texts from the Pudgalavāda tradition.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] These different traditions have some similarities, suggesting either interaction between groups or some common ground antedating the separation of the schools.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] In the Theravāda tradition it was held that the Abhidhamma was not a later addition, but rather was taught in the fourth week of Gautama Buddha's enlightenment.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The Theravada tradition is unique in regarding its Abhidharma as having been taught in its complete form by the Buddha as a single teaching, with the exception of the Kathavatthu, which contains material relating to later disputes and was held to only have been presented as an outline.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] According to their tradition, devas built a beautiful jeweled residence for the Buddha to the north-east of the Bodhi tree, where he meditated and delivered the Abhidharma teachings to gathered deities in the Trāyastriṃśa heaven, including his deceased mother Māyā.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The tradition holds that the Buddha gave daily summaries of the teachings given in the heavenly realm to the bhikkhu Sariputta, who passed them on.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The Sarvāstivāda-Vaibhāṣika held that the Buddha and his disciples taught the Abhidharma, but that it was scattered throughout the canon.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Only after his death was the Abhidharma compiled systematically by his elder disciples and was recited by Ananda at the first Buddhist council.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The Sautrāntika school ('those who rely on the sutras') rejected the status of the Abhidharma as being Buddhavacana (word of the Buddha), they held it was the work of different monks after his death, and that this was the reason different Abhidharma schools varied widely in their doctrines.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] However, this school still studied and debated on Abhidharma concepts and thus did not seek to question the method of the Abhidharma in its entirety.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Indeed, there were numerous Abhidharma texts written from an Abhidharma perspective.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The Abhidharma texts' field of inquiry extends to the entire Buddhadharma, since their goal was to outline, systematize and analyze all of the teachings.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Abhidharmic thought also extends beyond the sutras to cover new philosophical and psychological ground which is only implicit in sutras or not present at all.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] There are certain doctrines which were developed or even invented by the Abhidharmikas and these became grounds for the debates among the different early Buddhist schools.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The "base upon which the entire [Abhidhamma] system rests" is the 'dhamma theory' and this theory 'penetrated all the early schools'.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] For the Abhidharmikas, the ultimate components of existence, the elementary constituents of experience were called *dhammas* (Pali: *dhammas*).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] This concept has been variously translated as "factors" (Collett Cox), "psychic characteristics" (Bronkhorst), "phenomena" (Nyanaponika) and "psycho-physical events" (Ronkin).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The early Buddhist scriptures give various lists of the constituents of the person such as the five skandhas, the six or 18 dhatus, and the twelve sense bases.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] In Abhidhamma literature, these lists of dhammas systematically arranged and they were seen as the ultimate entities or momentary events which make up the fabric of people's experience of reality.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The idea was to create an exhaustive list of all possible phenomena that make up the world.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The conventional reality of substantial objects and persons is merely a conceptual construct imputed by the mind on a flux of dhammas.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] However, dhammas are never seen as individually separate entities, but are always dependently conditioned by other dhammas in a stream of momentary constellations of dhammas, constantly coming into being and vanishing, always in flux.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Perception and thinking is then seen as a combination of various dhammas.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Cittas (awareness events) are never experienced on their own, but are always intentional and hence accompanied by various mental factors (cetasikas), in a constantly flowing stream of experience occurrences.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Human experience is thus explained by a series of dynamic processes and their patterns of relationships with each other.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Buddhist Abhidhamma philosophers then sought to explain all experience by creating lists and matrices (matikas) of these dhammas, which varied by school.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] This dhamma is unconditioned it neither arises nor ceases due to causal interaction.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The Sarvastivada Abhidharma also used these, along with a fifth category: "factors dissociated from thought" (*cittaviprayuktasaṃskāra*).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The Sarvastivadas also included three dharmas in the fourth "unconditioned" category instead of just one, the dharma of space and two states of cessation.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The Abhidharma project was thus to provide a completely exhaustive account of every possible type of conscious experience in terms of its constituent factors and their relations.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The Theravada tradition holds that there were 82 types of possible dhammas – 82 types of occurrences in the experiential world, while the general Sarvastivada tradition eventually enumerated 75 dharma types.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] For the Abhidharmikas, truth was twofold and there are two ways of looking at reality.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] One way is the way of everyday experience and of normal worldly persons.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] This is the category of the nominal and the conceptual (paññatti), and is termed the conventional truth (saṃvṛti-satya).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] However, the way of the Abhidharma, and hence the way of enlightened persons like the Buddha, who have developed the true insight (vipassana), sees reality as the constant stream of collections of dharmas, and this way of seeing the world is ultimate truth (paramārtha-satya).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] As the Indian Buddhist Vasubandhu writes: "Anything the idea of which does not occur upon division or upon mental analysis, such as an object like a pot, that is a 'conceptual fiction'.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The ultimately real is otherwise." For Vasubandhu then, something is not the ultimately real if it 'disappears under analysis', but is merely conventional.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The ultimate goal of the Abhidharma is Nirvana and hence the Abhidharmikas systematized dhammas into those which are skillful (kusala), purify the mind and lead to liberation, and those which are unskillful and do not.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The Abhidharma then has a soteriological purpose, first and foremost and its goal is to support Buddhist practice and meditation.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The Abhidharmikas often used the term svabhāva (Pali: sabhāva) to explain the causal workings of dharmas.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] This term was used in different ways by the different Buddhist schools.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] This term does not appear in the sutras.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The examination of these characteristics was held to be extremely important, the Sarvastivada Mahavibhasa states "Abhidharma is [precisely] the analysis of the svalaksana and samanya-laksana of dharmas".
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] According to Peter Harvey, the Theravadin view of dharmas was that "'They are dhammas because they uphold their own nature [sabhaava].
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] They are dhammas because they are upheld by conditions or they are upheld according to their own nature' (Asl.39).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The *Visuddhimagga* of Buddhaghosa, the most influential classical Theravada treatise, states that not-self does not become apparent because it is concealed by "compactness" when one does not give attention to the various elements which make up the person.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The Sarvastivadins saw dharmas as the ultimately 'real entities' (sad-dravya), though they also held that dharmas were dependently originated.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] For the Sarvastivadins, a synonym for svabhava is avayaya (a 'part'), the smallest possible unit which cannot be analyzed into smaller parts and hence it is ultimately real as opposed to only conventionally real (such as a chariot or a person).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] However, the Sarvastivadins did not hold that dharmas were completely independent of each other, as the Mahavibhasa states: "conditioned dharmas are weak in their intrinsic nature, they can accomplish their activities only through mutual dependence" and "they have no sovereignty (aisvarya).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Svabhava in the early Abhidhamma texts was then not a term which meant ontological independence, metaphysical essence or underlying substance, but simply referred to their characteristics, which are dependent on other conditions and qualities.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] According to Ronkin: "In the early Sarvāstivāda exegetical texts, then, svabhāva is used as an atemporal, invariable criterion determining what a dharma is, not necessarily that a dharma exists.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The Sautrantika school accepted the doctrine of svabhāva as referring to the distinctive or main characteristic of a dharma, but rejected the view that they exist in all three times .
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The Buddhist philosopher Dharmakirti uses the concept of svabhāva, though he interprets it as being based on causal powers.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Other early Buddhist schools did not accept the svabhava concept, instead positing a kind of nominalism or conceptualism (*prajñaptivada*).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] This view was widespread among the Mahasamghika Nikaya.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] One school was even called "Prajñaptivada" because of their denial of the ultimate reality of all dharmas and their view that all dharmas are characterized by *prajñapti* (provisional designation or fictitious construction).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Another school called the Vainasikas also held that all dharmas were without svabhava.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] According to Paramārtha (499–569), another school, the Ekavyavahārikas held "that both the mundane and the supramundane factors [dharmas] are merely nominal (*prajñapti*).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] They therefore claimed that all factors have no real essence, and that hence the same name applies to all [dharmas]." This helps to explain their name as “Ekavyavahārika” (those who propound the single meaning).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Paramārtha also notes that the Lokottaravāda school held "that the mundane factors have arisen from perversion (viparyāsa) and are only nominal (prajñapti)." However, in contrast to the other schools, they also held that the supramundane dharmas (nirvana etc.) were not nominal but real.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] This view that dharmas are empty or void is also found in the *Lokānuvartana-sūtra* (‘The Sutra of Conformity with the World’, Taisho No.807) which survives in Chinese and Tibetan translation, and may have been a scripture of the Purvasailas, which was a sub-school of the Mahasamghika.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Another important project for the Abhidharmikas was to outline a theory of causality, especially of how momentary dharmas relate to each other through causes and conditions.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The Sarvastivadin analysis focused on six causes (*hetu*), four conditions (*pratyaya*) and five effects (*phala*).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Dhammajoti, for the Sarvastivada school, 'causal efficacy is the central criterion for the reality/existence (astitva) of a dharma' and hence they were also sometimes called the 'Hetuvada' school.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] A dharma is real because it is a cause and it has effects, if it had no causal efficacy, it would not exist.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The last book of the Pali Abhidhamma, the Patthana, sets out the main Theravada theory on conditioned relations and causality.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The Patthana is an exhaustive examination of the conditioned nature (Paticcasamupada) of all dhammas.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The introduction begins with a detailed list of 24 specific types of conditioned relationships (paccaya) that may pertain between different factors.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The majority of these conditions have counterparts in the Sarvāstivāda Abhidharma.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The Pali Abhidhammatthasangaha reduces them all to four main types.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The Sautrāntika school used a theory of 'seeds' (bīja) in the mental continuum to explain causal interaction between past and present dharmas, this theory was later developed by the Yogacara school in their theory of “storehouse consciousness” (ālayavijñāna).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] A prominent argument between the Abhidharmikas was on the Philosophy of time.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The Sarvāstivādin tradition held the view (expressed in the Vijñanakaya) that dharmas exist in all three times – past, present, future; hence the name of their school means "theory of all exists".
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The Sautrāntika, Vibhajyavāda and Theravada schools argued against this eternalist view in favor of presentism (only the present moment exists).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] This argument was so central, that north Indian Buddhist schools were often named according to their philosophical position.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] "Those who hold 'all exists' — the past, the present and the future — belong to the Sarvāstivāda.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Vasubandhu initially wrote in favor of Sarvāstivāda, and later critiqued this position.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The Sarvāstivāda-Vaibhāṣika also held an atomistic conception of time which divided time into discrete indivisible moments (kṣaṇa) and saw all events as lasting only for a minute instant (and yet also existing in all three times).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Theravadins also held a theory of momentariness (Khāṇavāda), but it was less ontological than Sarvāstivāda and more focused on the psychological aspects of time.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The Theravada divided every dhamma into three different instants of origination (uppādakkhaṇa), endurance (ṭhitikkhaṇa) and cessation (bhaṅgakkhaṇa).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] They also held that only mental events were momentary, material events could endure for longer.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] A key problem which the Abhidharmikas wished to tackle was the question of how rebirth and karma works if there is no self to be reborn apart from the five aggregates.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The Patthana includes the earliest Pali canonical reference to an important answer to this question: bhavanga, or 'life-continuum'.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] This problem was also taken up by a group of Buddhist schools termed the Pudgalavadins or "Personalists" which included the Vātsīputrīya, the Dharmottarīya, the Bhadrayānīya, the Sammitiya and the Shannagarika.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] These schools posited the existence of a 'person' (pudgala) or self, which had a real existence that was not reducible to streams and collections of dharmas.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] They also often used other terms to refer to this real 'self', such as 'Atman' and 'Jiva' which are words for the immortal soul in Hinduism and Jainism respectively.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] They seemed to have held that the 'self' was part of a fifth category of existence, the “inexpressible”.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] This was a radically different view than the not-self view held by the mainstream Buddhist schools and this theory was a major point of controversy and was thoroughly attacked by other Buddhist schools such as the Theravadins, Sarvastivadins and later Mahayanists.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The Sarvastivadin Abhidharmikas also developed the novel idea of an intermediate state between death and the next rebirth.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The Purvasaila, Sammitiya, Vatsiputriya, and later Mahisasaka schools accepted this view, while the Theravadins, Vibhajyavada, Mahasanghika, and the Sariputrabhidharmasastra of the Dharmaguptakas rejected it.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Some Abhidharmikas such as the Sarvastivadins also defended an atomic theory.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] However unlike the Hindu Vaisheshika school, Abhidharmic atoms (paramannu) are not permanent, but momentary.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The Vaibhasika held that an atom is the smallest analyzable unit of matter (rupa), hence it is a 'conceptual atom' (prajnapti-paramanu), though this also corresponds to a real existing thing.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] "An atom (paramänu) is the smallest rüpa.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] It cannot be cut, broken, penetrated; it cannot be taken up, abandoned, ridden on, stepped on, struck or dragged.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] It is neither long nor short, square nor round, regular nor irregular, convex nor concave.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] It has no smaller parts; it cannot be decomposed, cannot be seen, heard, smelled, touched.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The *Abhidhamma Piṭaka* is the third pitaka, or basket, of the Tipitaka (Sanskrit: *Tripiṭaka*), the canon of the Theravāda school.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The *Abhidhamma Piṭaka*, like the rest of the Theravāda *Tipiṭaka*, was orally transmitted until the 1st century BCE.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Due to famines and constant wars, the monks responsible for recording the oral tradition felt that there was a risk of portions of the canon being lost so the Abhidhamma was written down for the first time along with the rest of the Pāli Canon in the first century BCE.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The books of the *Abhidhamma Piṭaka* were translated into English in the 20th century and published by the Pāli Text Society.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] In addition to the canonical Abhidharma, Pali literature includes a variety of Abhidhamma commentaries and introductory manuals written after the compilation of the *Abhidhamma Piṭaka*.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] These post-canonical texts attempted to expand and further clarify the analysis presented in the Abhidhamma.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The most influential of these commentaries are those of Buddhaghosa (c.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] 5th century) a South Indian exegete and philosopher who moved to Sri Lanka and wrote various commentaries and treatises in Pali.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] His *Visuddhimagga* ("Path of Purification") is a comprehensive manual of Buddhist practice that also contains an overview of the Abhidhamma.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] This text remains one of the most popular Abhidhamma influenced texts in Theravada.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Sri Lankan Theravādins also composed shorter introductory manuals to the Abhidhamma.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The most popular and widely used of these remains the *Abhidhammatthasangaha* (*Compendium of the Topics of the Abhidharma*) by Anuruddha (circa 8th to 12th century).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] A further period of medieval Sri Lankan scholarship also produced a series of texts called the *sub-commentaries* (which are commentaries to the commentaries).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Abhidhamma remains a living tradition in Theravāda nations today and modern Abhidhamma works continue to be written in modern languages such as Burmese and Sinhala.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Abhidhamma studies are particularly stressed in Myanmar, where it has been the primary subject of study since around the 17th century.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] One of the most important figures in modern Myanmar Buddhism, Ledi Sayadaw (1846–1923), was well known for his writings on Abhidhamma (especially his commentary on the *Abhidhammatthasangaha,* called the *Paramatthadipanitika*).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The most influential Indian Abhidharma tradition was that of the Sarvāstivāda Vaibhāṣika school, which was dominant in North India, especially Kashmir and also in Bactria and Gandhara.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] This is the Abhidharma tradition that is studied in East Asian Buddhism and also in Tibetan Buddhism.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Like the Theravada Abhidharma, the Sarvāstivāda *Abhidharma Pitaka* also consists of seven texts, but they are quite different works, unlike the Sarvāstivāda Agamas, which are very close, often identical, to the suttas of the Theravada *Sutta Pitaka*.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] According to Frauwallner however, the two Abhidharma collections share an "ancient core", which is basically an early doctrinal list of dharmas.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The core canonical work of this school, the *Jñānaprasthāna* ('Foundation of Knowledge'), also known as *Aṣṭaskandha* or *Aṣṭagrantha,* was said to be composed by master Kātyāyanīputra.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] This became the basis for the *Abhidharma Mahāvibhāṣa Śāstra* ("Great Commentary"), an encyclopedic work which became the central text of the Vaibhāṣika tradition who became the Kasmiri Sarvāstivāda Orthodoxy under the patronage of the Kushan Empire.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Despite numerous variations and doctrinal disagreements within the tradition, most Sarvāstivāda-Vaibhāṣikas were united in their acceptance of the doctrine of "*sarvāstitva*" (all exists), which says that all phenomena in the three times (past, present and future) can be said to exist.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Another defining Vaibhāṣika doctrine was that of simultaneous causation (*sahabhū-hetu*).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] In addition to the core Vaibhāṣika Abhidharma literature, a variety of expository texts or treatises were written to serve as overviews and introductions to the Abhidharma.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The oldest one of these was the *Abhidharma-hṛdaya-sastra* (*The Heart of Abhidharma*), by the Tocharian Dharmasresthin, (c.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] This text became the model for most of the later treatises.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The most influential of these treatises however, is certainly the *Abhidharmakośabhāsya* (*Treasury of Higher Knowledge*, 5th century), a series of verses and accompanying commentary by Vasubandhu.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] It often critiques Vaibhāṣika views from a Sautrantika perspective.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The Sautrantikas were a dissent group within the Sarvāstivāda tradition that rejected many of the core Vaibhāṣika views.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] This text remains the main source for Abhidharma in Indo-Tibetan and East Asian Buddhism.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The most mature and refined form of Vaibhāṣika philosophy can be seen in the work of master Saṃghabhadra (ca fifth century CE), "undoubtedly one of the most brilliant Abhidharma masters in India".
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] His two main works, the **Nyāyānusāra* (*Shun zhengli lun* 順正理論) and the **Abhidharmasamayapradīpikā* (*Apidamo xian zong lun* 阿毘達磨顯宗論), are key sources of late Vaibhāṣika Abhidharma.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The *Śāriputra Abhidharma Śāstra* (舍利弗阿毘曇論 *Shèlìfú Āpítán Lùn*) (T.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] 1548) is a complete abhidharma text that is thought to come from the Dharmaguptaka sect.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The only complete edition of this text is that in Chinese.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Sanskrit fragments from this text have been found in Bamiyan, Afghanistan, and are now part of the Schøyen Collection (MS 2375/08).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The manuscripts at this find are thought to have been part of a monastery library of the Mahāsāṃghika Lokottaravāda sect.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Several Pudgalavada Abhidharma type texts also survive in Chinese, such as the *Traidharmakasastra* (Taisho no.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] 15c-30a) and the *Sammatiyanikayasastra.* These texts contain traditional Abhidharma type lists and doctrines, but they also expound and defend the Pudgalavada doctrine of the "person" (*pudgala*).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Many Abhidharma texts have been lost—likely more than have survived.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] This includes texts brought from India by Xuanzang belonging to a variety of Indian schools that were never translated into Chinese.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Many Abhidharma sastras discovered among the Gandharan Buddhist texts have no parallel in existing Indic languages or Chinese or Tibetan translation, suggesting the former breadth of Abhidharma literature.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] According to some sources, abhidharma was not accepted as canonical by the Mahāsāṃghika school.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The Theravādin *Dīpavaṃsa*, for example, records that the Mahāsāṃghikas had no abhidharma.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] However, other sources indicate that there were such collections of abhidharma.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] During the early 5th century, the Chinese pilgrim Faxian is said to have found a Mahāsāṃghika Abhidharma at a monastery in Pāṭaliputra.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] When Xuanzang visited Dhānyakaṭaka, he wrote that the monks of this region were Mahāsāṃghikas, and mentions the Pūrvaśailas specifically.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Near Dhānyakaṭaka, he met two Mahāsāṃghika bhikṣus and studied Mahāsāṃghika abhidharma with them for several months, during which time they also studied various Mahāyāna śāstras together under Xuanzang's direction.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] On the basis of textual evidence as well as inscriptions at Nāgārjunakoṇḍā, Joseph Walser concludes that at least some Mahāsāṃghika sects probably had an abhidharma collection, and that it likely contained five or six books.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The *Tattvasiddhi Śāstra* ("the treatise that accomplishes reality"; Chinese: 成實論, *Chéngshílun*), is an extant Abhidharma text which was popular in Chinese Buddhism.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] This Abhidharma is now contained in the Chinese Buddhist canon, in sixteen fascicles (Taishō Tripiṭaka 1646).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Its authorship is attributed to Harivarman, a third-century monk from central India.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] This work may belong to the Mahāsāṃghika Bahuśrutīya school or to the Sautrāntika school.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Paramārtha cites this Bahuśrutīya abhidharma as containing a combination of Hīnayāna and Mahāyāna doctrines, and Joseph Walser agrees that this assessment is correct.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] Ian Charles Harris also characterizes the text as a synthesis of Hīnayāna and Mahāyāna, and notes that its doctrines are very close to those in Mādhyamaka and Yogācāra works.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The *Tattvasiddhi Śāstra* maintained great popularity in Chinese Buddhism, and even lead to the formation of its own school of Buddhism in China, the *Chéngshí school* (成實宗), which was founded in 412 CE.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The *Chéngshí* School taught a progression of twenty-seven stations for cultivating realization, based upon the teachings of this text.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] They took Harivarman as its founder in India, and Kumārajīva as the school's founder in China.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] The *Chéngshí* School is counted among the ten schools of Tang dynasty Buddhism.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] From China, the *Chéngshí* School was transmitted to Japan in 625 CE, where it was known as *Jōjitsu-shu* (成實宗).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p01] This school is known as one of the six great schools of Japanese Buddhism in the Nara period (710–794 CE).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p02] Another complete system of Abhidharma thought is elaborated in certain works of the Mahāyāna Yogācāra tradition (which mainly evolved out of the Sarvāstivāda Abhidharma).
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p02] This Yogācāra Abhidharma can be found in the works of figures like Asanga, Vasubandhu, Sthiramati, Dharmapāla, Śīlabhadra, Xuanzang (Hsüan-tsang), and Vinītadeva.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p02] Yogācārins developed an Abhidharma literature set within a Mahāyāna framework.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p02] The *Prajñāpāramitā* sutras and associated literature are influenced by Abhidharma.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p02] These texts make use of Abhidharma categories (like the dharma theory), and adopt them or critique them in different ways.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p02] According to Edward Conze, the *Prajñāpāramitā* sutras were meant to be a criticism of the view held by some of the Abhidharmikas which saw dharmas as real.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p02] Conze also notes that the later *Prajñāpāramitā* sutras have been expanded by the insertion of various doctrinal Abhidharma lists.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p02] There is also plenty of Abhidharma material (mainly Sarvāstivāda) in the *Dà zhìdù lùn* (*The Treatise on the Great Prajñāpāramitā*; Chinese: 大智度論, *Mahāprajñāpāramitāupadeśa** Taishō Tripiṭaka no.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p02] The *Dà zhìdù lùn* was translated into Chinese by Kumārajīva (344–413 CE) and his student Sengrui.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p02] The work claims it is written by Nāgārjuna (c.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p02] 2nd century), but various scholars such as Étienne Lamotte and Paul Demiéville, have questioned this, holding that the author was instead a Sarvāstivāda monk learned in Abhidharma who became a Mahāyānist and wrote this text.
[src:ashoka/abhidharma-p02] It is a very influential text in East Asian Buddhism.
[src:ashoka/abp-news] It won the Best Hindi News Channel award in the 21st edition of the Indian Television Academy Awards in 2022.
[src:ashoka/abp-news] ABP News was launched as STAR News on 18 February 1998 by satellite television provider Star India in partnership with the NDTV media company, with the latter producing the channel's programming.
[src:ashoka/abp-news] Initially, a bilingual channel broadcasting in both English and Hindi, its programming turned Hindi-only since 2003, when Star's deal with NDTV expired.
[src:ashoka/abp-news] In that same year, the Indian government introduced a guideline limiting foreign equity in the national news business to 26%.
[src:ashoka/abp-news] As Star India was a wholly owned subsidiary of Hong Kong–based company Satellite Television Asia Region Ltd.
[src:ashoka/abp-news] (Star TV), it entered into a joint venture with the Ananda Bazar Patrika Group (ABP Group) to form a new company, Media Content and Communications Services Pvt.
[src:ashoka/abp-news] (MCCS), which took control of Star News's operations.
[src:ashoka/abp-news] ABP held a 74% majority stake while Star India reduced its participation with the remaining 26%.
[src:ashoka/abp-news] On 16 April 2012, ABP Group and Star India announced the end of the Star brand licensing agreement.
[src:ashoka/abp-news] In addition, the company sold its minority stake in MCCS to ABP Group, which in turn renamed the channel to ABP News.
[src:ashoka/abp-news] The change was also replicated on other regional news channels operated by MCCS such as Bengali-language Star Ananda and Marathi-language Star Majha, which were renamed as ABP Ananda and ABP Majha, respectively.
[src:ashoka/abp-news] A Punjabi-language channel, ABP Sanjha was granted licence approval in 2014 and launched in that year.
[src:ashoka/abp-news] A Gujarati-language channel, ABP Asmita, was launched on 1 January 2016.
[src:ashoka/abp-news] In November 2016, Avinash Pandey became a chief operating officer (COO) of ABP News.
[src:ashoka/abp-news] All of ABP's channels, including ABP News, were gradually revamped throughout the second half of 2020, beginning with the renaming of parent-subsidiary ABP News Network to ABP Network in July 2020.
[src:ashoka/abp-news] A further rebranding, which affected the channels themselves, took place in the morning of 16 December 2020, with the launch of simpler, more modern logos and a new graphics package developed by Saffron Brand Consultants for all of ABP's channels.
[src:ashoka/abp-news] Additionally, ABP News acquired new equipment able to record content at 1080p and launched its own HD feed; the channel's SD feed turned into a downscaled, 16:9 widescreen version of the HD feed.
[src:ashoka/abp-news] Prior to the HD feed launch, ABP News had launched a test HD feed in February of that same year, exclusively on streaming service Disney+ Hotstar and on ABP's online platforms, which was basically an upscaled version of the SD channel airing 4:3 content stretched to fill the 16:9 screen.
[src:ashoka/abp-news] Although ABP Network's regional language channels were also rebranded, they remained airing at 4:3 standard definition.
[src:ashoka/abp-news] In 2018, former host Punya Prasun Bajpai stated that when he criticized the performance of one of prime minister Narendra Modi's projects directed towards poor farmers in his television show *Masterstroke*, ABP News' satellite broadcasting was disrupted each time the program was aired.
[src:ashoka/abp-news] Former employees reported that the channel owners had pressured the host, Punya Prasun Bajpai, to quit the company.
[src:ashoka/abp-news] After his resignation, these technical issues immediately stopped.
[src:ashoka/abp-news] Another host, Abhisar Sharma, who challenged Modi's public safety strategies on ABP News, was fired that same day.
[src:ashoka/abp-news] He also said he was under pressure to leave.
[src:ashoka/abp-news] The channel has been criticised for being biased and aligning with Hindutva, the ideology of the ruling Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) government.
[src:ashoka/abp-news] It has been considered to be a part of "Godi media".
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The Edicts of Ashoka state that during his eighth regnal year (c.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] 260 BCE), he conquered Kalinga after a brutal war.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Ashoka subsequently devoted himself to the propagation of "dhamma" or righteous conduct, the major theme of the edicts.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Ashoka's edicts suggest that a few years after the Kalinga War, he was gradually drawn towards Buddhism.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The Buddhist legends credit Ashoka with establishing a large number of stupas, patronising the Third Buddhist council, supporting Buddhist missionaries, and making generous donations to the sangha.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Ashoka's existence as a historical emperor had almost been forgotten, but since the decipherment in the 19th century of sources written in the Brahmi script, Ashoka holds a reputation as one of the greatest Indian emperors.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The State Emblem of the modern Republic of India is an adaptation of the Lion Capital of Ashoka.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Ashoka's wheel, the Ashoka Chakra, is adopted at the centre of the National Flag of India.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Information about Ashoka comes from his inscriptions, other inscriptions that mention him or are possibly from his reign, and ancient literature, especially Buddhist texts.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] These sources often contradict each other, although various historians have attempted to correlate their testimony.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Ashoka's inscriptions are the earliest self-representations of imperial power in the Indian subcontinent.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] However, these inscriptions are focused mainly on the topic of *dhamma*, and provide little information regarding other aspects of the Maurya state or society.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Even on the topic of *dhamma*, the content of these inscriptions cannot be taken at face value.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] In the words of American academic John S.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Strong, it is sometimes helpful to think of Ashoka's messages as propaganda by a politician whose aim is to present a favourable image of himself and his administration, rather than record historical facts.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] A small number of other inscriptions also provide some information about Ashoka.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] For example, he finds a mention in the 2nd-century Junagadh rock inscription of Rudradaman.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] An inscription discovered at Sirkap mentions a lost word beginning with "Priyadari", which is theorised to be Ashoka's title "Priyadarshi" since it has been written in Aramaic of the 3rd century BCE, although this is not certain.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Some other inscriptions, such as the Sohgaura copper plate inscription and the Mahasthan inscription, have been tentatively dated to Ashoka's period by some scholars, although others contest this.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Much of the information about Ashoka comes from Buddhist legends, which present him as a great, ideal emperor.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] These legends appear in texts that are not contemporary to Ashoka and were composed by Buddhist authors, who used various stories to illustrate the impact of their faith on Ashoka.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] This makes it necessary to exercise caution while relying on them for historical information.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Among modern scholars, opinions range from downright dismissal of these legends as mythological to acceptance of all historical portions that seem plausible.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The Buddhist legends about Ashoka exist in several languages, including Sanskrit, Pali, Tibetan, Chinese, Burmese, Khmer, Sinhala, Thai, Lao, and Khotanese.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] There are several significant differences between the two traditions.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] For example, the Sri Lankan tradition emphasizes Ashoka's role in convening the Third Buddhist council, and his dispatch of several missionaries to distant regions, including his son Mahinda to Sri Lanka.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] However, the North Indian tradition makes no mention of these events.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] It describes other events not found in the Sri Lankan tradition, such as a story about another son named Kunala.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Even while narrating the common stories, the two traditions diverge in several ways.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] For example, both *Ashokavadana* and *Mahavamsa* mention that Ashoka's empress Tishyarakshita had the Bodhi Tree destroyed.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] In *Ashokavadana*, the empress manages to have the tree healed after she realises her mistake.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] In the *Mahavamsa*, she permanently destroys the tree, but only after a branch of the tree has been transplanted in Sri Lanka.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] In another story, both the texts describe Ashoka's unsuccessful attempts to collect a relic of Gautama Buddha from Ramagrama.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] In *Ashokavadana*, he fails to do so because he cannot match the devotion of the Nāgas who hold the relic; however, in the *Mahavamsa*, he fails to do so because the Buddha had destined the relic to be enshrined by King Dutthagamani of Sri Lanka.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Using such stories, the *Mahavamsa* glorifies Sri Lanka as the new preserve of Buddhism.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Numismatic, sculptural, and archaeological evidence supplements research on Ashoka.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Ashoka's name appears in the lists of Mauryan emperors in the various Puranas.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] However, these texts do not provide further details about him, as their Brahmanical authors were not patronized by the Mauryans.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Other texts, such as the *Arthashastra* and *Indica* of Megasthenes, which provide general information about the Maurya period, can also be used to make inferences about Ashoka's reign.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] However, the *Arthashastra* is a normative text that focuses on an ideal rather than a historical state, and its dating to the Mauryan period is a subject of debate.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The *Indica* is a lost work, and only parts of it survive in the form of paraphrases in later writings.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The 12th-century text *Rajatarangini* mentions a Kashmiri king Ashoka of Gonandiya dynasty who built several stupas: some scholars, such as Aurel Stein, have identified this king with the Maurya emperor Ashoka; others, such as Ananda W.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Guruge dismiss this identification as inaccurate.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The name "A-shoka" literally means "without sorrow".
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] According to an *Ashokavadana* legend, his mother gave him this name because his birth removed her sorrows.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The name Priyadasi is associated with Ashoka in the 3rd–4th century CE *Dipavamsa*.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The term literally means "he who regards amiably", or "of gracious mien" (Sanskrit: Priya-darshi).
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] It may have been a regnal name adopted by Ashoka.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] A version of this name is used for Ashoka in Greek-language inscriptions: βασιλεὺς Πιοδασσης ("Basileus Piodassēs").
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Ashoka's inscriptions mention his title *Devanampiya* (Sanskrit: *Devanampriya*, "Beloved of the Gods").
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The identification of Devanampiya and Ashoka as the same person is established by the Maski and Gujarra inscriptions, which use both these terms for the king.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The title was adopted by other kings, including the contemporary king Devanampiya Tissa of Anuradhapura and Ashoka's descendant Dasharatha Maurya.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The exact date of Ashoka's birth is not certain, as the extant contemporary Indian texts did not record such details.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] It is known that he lived in the 3rd century BCE, as his inscriptions mention several contemporary rulers whose dates are known with more certainty, such as Antiochus II Theos, Ptolemy II Philadelphus, Antigonus II Gonatas, Magas of Cyrene, and Alexander (of Epirus or Corinth).
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Thus, Ashoka must have been born sometime in the late 4th century BCE or early 3rd century BCE (c.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] 304 BCE), and ascended the throne around 269-268 BCE.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Ashoka's own inscriptions are fairly detailed but make no mention of his ancestors.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Other sources, such as the Puranas and the *Mahavamsa* state that his father was the Mauryan emperor Bindusara, and his grandfather was Chandragupta – the founder of the Empire.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The *Ashokavadana* also names his father as Bindusara, but traces his ancestry to Buddha's contemporary king Bimbisara, through Ajatashatru, Udayin, Munda, Kakavarnin, Sahalin, Tulakuchi, Mahamandala, Prasenajit, and Nanda.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The 16th-century Tibetan monk Taranatha, whose account is a distorted version of the earlier traditions, describes Ashoka as son of king Nemita of Champarana from the daughter of a merchant.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] According to the 2nd-century historian Appian, Chandragupta entered into a marital alliance with the Greek ruler Seleucus I Nicator, which has led to speculation that either Chandragupta or his son Bindusara married a Greek princess.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] However, there is no evidence that Ashoka's mother or grandmother was Greek, and most historians have dismissed the idea.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Ashoka's own inscriptions do not describe his early life, and much of the information on this topic comes from apocryphal legends written hundreds of years after him.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] While these legends include obviously fictitious details such as narratives of Ashoka's past lives, they have some plausible historical information about Ashoka's period.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] According to the *Ashokavadana*, when Ashoka was young, his father hated him for his rough and unappealing skin.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] One day, Bindusara, his father, asked the ascetic Pingala-vatsajiva to determine which of his sons was worthy of being his successor.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] He asked all the princes to assemble at the Garden of the Golden Pavilion on the ascetic's advice.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Ashoka was reluctant to go because his father disliked him, but his mother convinced him to do so.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] When minister Radhagupta saw Ashoka leaving the capital for the Garden, he offered to provide the prince with an imperial elephant for the travel.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] At the Garden, Pingala-vatsajiva examined the princes and realised that Ashoka would be the next emperor.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] To avoid annoying Bindusara, the ascetic refused to name the successor.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Instead, he said that one who had the best mount, seat, drink, vessel and food would be the next king; each time, Ashoka declared that he met the criterion.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Later, he told Ashoka's mother that her son would be the next emperor, and on her advice, left the empire to avoid Bindusara's wrath.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] While legends suggest that Bindusara disliked Ashoka's ugly appearance, they also state that Bindusara gave him important responsibilities, such as suppressing a revolt in Takshashila (according to north Indian tradition) and governing Ujjain (according to Sri Lankan tradition).
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] This suggests that Bindusara was impressed by the other qualities of the prince.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Another possibility is that he sent Ashoka to distant regions to keep him away from the imperial capital.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] According to the *Ashokavadana*, Bindusara dispatched prince Ashoka to suppress a rebellion in the city of Takshashila (present-day Bhir Mound in Pakistan).
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] This episode is not mentioned in the Sri Lankan tradition, which instead states that Bindusara sent Ashoka to govern Ujjain.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Two other Buddhist texts – *Ashoka-sutra* and *Kunala-sutra* – state that Bindusara appointed Ashoka as a viceroy in Gandhara (where Takshashila was located), not Ujjain.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The *Ashokavadana* states that Bindusara provided Ashoka with a fourfold-army (comprising cavalry, elephants, chariots and infantry) but refused to provide any weapons for this army.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Ashoka declared that weapons would appear before him if he was worthy of being an emperor, and then, the deities emerged from the earth and provided weapons to the army.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] When Ashoka reached Takshashila, the citizens welcomed him and told him that their rebellion was only against the evil ministers, not the emperor.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Sometime later, Ashoka was similarly welcomed in the Khasa territory and the gods declared that he would go on to conquer the whole earth.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Takshashila was a prosperous and geopolitically influential city, and historical evidence proves that by Ashoka's time, it was well-connected to the Mauryan capital Pataliputra by the *Uttarapatha* trade route.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] However, no extant contemporary source mentions the Takshashila rebellion, and none of Ashoka's records state that he ever visited the city.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] That said, the historicity of the legend about Ashoka's involvement in the Takshashila rebellion may be corroborated by an Aramaic-language inscription discovered at Sirkap near Taxila.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The inscription includes a name that begins with the letters "prydr", and most scholars restore it as "Priyadarshi", which was the title of Ashoka.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Another evidence of Ashoka's connection to the city may be the name of the Dharmarajika Stupa near Taxila; the name suggests that it was built by Ashoka ("Dharma-raja").
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The story about the deities miraculously bringing weapons to Ashoka may be the text's way of deifying Ashoka; or indicating that Bindusara – who disliked Ashoka – wanted him to fail in Takshashila.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] According to the *Mahavamsa*, Bindusara appointed Ashoka as the Viceroy of Avantirastra (present day Ujjain district), which was an important administrative and commercial province in central India.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] This tradition is corroborated by the Saru Maru inscription discovered in central India; this inscription states that he visited the place as a prince.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Ashoka's own rock edict mentions the presence of a prince viceroy at Ujjain during his reign, which further supports the tradition that he himself served as a viceroy at Ujjain.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Pataliputra was connected to Ujjain by multiple routes in Ashoka's time, and on the way, Ashoka entourage may have encamped at Rupnath, where his inscription has been found.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] According to the Sri Lankan tradition, Ashoka visited Vidisha, where he fell in love with a beautiful woman on his way to Ujjain.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] According to the *Dipamvamsa* and *Mahamvamsa*, the woman was Devi – the daughter of a merchant.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] According to the *Mahabodhi-vamsa*, she was Vidisha-Mahadevi and belonged to the Shakya clan of Gautama Buddha.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The Buddhist chroniclers may have fabricated the Shakya connection to connect Ashoka's family to Buddha.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The Buddhist texts allude to her being a Buddhist in her later years but do not describe her conversion to Buddhism.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Therefore, it is likely that she was already a Buddhist when she met Ashoka.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The *Mahavamsa* states that Devi gave birth to Ashoka's son Mahinda in Ujjain, and two years later, to a daughter named Sanghamitta.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] According to the *Mahavamsa*, Ashoka's son Mahinda was ordained at the age of 20 years, during the sixth year of Ashoka's reign.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] That means Mahinda must have been 14 years old when Ashoka ascended the throne.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Even if Mahinda was born when Ashoka was as young as 20 years old, Ashoka must have ascended the throne at 34 years, which means he must have served as a viceroy for several years.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Legends suggest that Ashoka was not the crown prince, and his ascension on the throne was disputed.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The *Mahavamsa* states that when Bindusara fell sick, Ashoka returned to Pataliputra from Ujjain and gained control of the capital.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] After his father's death, Ashoka had his eldest brother killed and ascended the throne.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The text also states that Ashoka killed ninety-nine of his half-brothers, including Sumana.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The *Dipavamsa* states that he killed a hundred of his brothers and was crowned four years later.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The *Vamsatthapakasini* adds that an Ajivika ascetic had predicted this massacre based on the interpretation of a dream of Ashoka's mother.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] According to these accounts, only Ashoka's uterine brother Tissa was spared.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Other sources name the surviving brother Vitashoka, Vigatashoka, Sudatta (So-ta-to in *A-yi-uang-chuan*), or Sugatra (Siu-ka-tu-lu in *Fen-pie-kung-te-hun*).
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The figures such as 99 and 100 are exaggerated and seem to be a way of stating that Ashoka killed several of his brothers.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Taranatha states that Ashoka, who was an illegitimate son of his predecessor, killed six legitimate princes to ascend the throne.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] It is possible that Ashoka was not the rightful heir to the throne and killed a brother (or brothers) to acquire the throne.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] However, the Buddhist sources have exaggerated the story, in their attempts to portray him as evil before his conversion to Buddhism.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] 5 mentions officers whose duties include supervising the welfare of "the families of his brothers, sisters, and other relatives".
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] This suggests that more than one of his brothers survived his ascension.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] However, some scholars oppose this suggestion, arguing that the inscription talks only about the *families* of his brothers, not the brothers themselves.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] According to the Sri Lankan texts *Mahavamsa* and the *Dipavamsa*, Ashoka ascended the throne 218 years after the death of Gautama Buddha and ruled for 37 years.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The date of the Buddha's death is itself a matter of debate, and the North Indian tradition states that Ashoka ruled a hundred years after the Buddha's death, which has led to further debates about the date.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Assuming that the Sri Lankan tradition is correct, and assuming that the Buddha died in 483 BCE – a date proposed by several scholars – Ashoka must have ascended the throne in 265 BCE.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The Puranas state that Ashoka's father Bindusara reigned for 25 years, not 28 years as specified in the Sri Lankan tradition.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] If this is true, Ashoka's ascension can be dated three years earlier, to 268 BCE.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Alternatively, if the Sri Lankan tradition is correct, but if we assume that the Buddha died in 486 BCE (a date supported by the Cantonese Dotted Record), Ashoka's ascension can be dated to 268 BCE.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The *Mahavamsa* states that Ashoka consecrated himself as the emperor four years after becoming a sovereign.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] This interregnum can be explained assuming that he fought a war of succession with other sons of Bindusara during these four years.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The *Ashokavadana* contains a story about Ashoka's minister Yashas hiding the sun with his hand.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Eggermont theorised that this story was a reference to a partial solar eclipse that was seen in northern India on 4 May 249 BCE.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] According to the *Ashokavadana*, Ashoka went on a pilgrimage to various Buddhist sites sometime after this eclipse.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Ashoka's Rummindei pillar inscription states that he visited Lumbini during his 21st regnal year.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Assuming this visit was a part of the pilgrimage described in the text, and assuming that Ashoka visited Lumbini around 1–2 years after the solar eclipse, the ascension date of 268–269 BCE seems more likely.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] However, this theory is not universally accepted.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Strong, the event described in the *Ashokavadana* has nothing to do with chronology, and Eggermont's interpretation grossly ignores the literary and religious context of the legend.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Both Sri Lankan and North Indian traditions assert that Ashoka was a violent person before Buddhism.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The 5th-century Chinese traveller Faxian states that Ashoka personally visited the underworld to study torture methods there and then invented his methods.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The 7th-century traveller Xuanzang claims to have seen a pillar marking the site of Ashoka's "Hell".
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The *Mahavamsa* also briefly alludes to Ashoka's cruelty, stating that Ashoka was earlier called Chandashoka because of his evil deeds but came to be called Dharmashoka because of his pious acts after his conversion to Buddhism.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] However, unlike the north Indian tradition, the Sri Lankan texts do not mention any specific evil deeds performed by Ashoka, except his killing of 99 of his brothers.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Such descriptions of Ashoka as an evil person before his conversion to Buddhism appear to be a fabrication of the Buddhist authors, who attempted to present the change that Buddhism brought to him as a miracle.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] In an attempt to dramatise this change, such legends exaggerate Ashoka's past wickedness and his piousness after the conversion.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Ashoka's inscriptions mention that he conquered the Kalinga region during his 8th regnal year: the destruction caused during the war made him repent violence, and in the subsequent years, he was drawn towards Buddhism.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] On the other hand, the Sri Lankan tradition suggests that Ashoka was already a devoted Buddhist by his 8th regnal year, converted to Buddhism during his 4th regnal year, and constructed 84,000 viharas during his 5th–7th regnal years.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The Buddhist legends make no mention of the Kalinga campaign.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Based on Sri Lankan tradition, some scholars, such as Eggermont, believe Ashoka converted to Buddhism *before* the Kalinga war.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Critics of this theory argue that if Ashoka were already a Buddhist, he would not have waged the violent Kalinga War.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Eggermont explains this anomaly by theorising that Ashoka had his own interpretation of the "Middle Way".
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Some earlier writers believed that Ashoka *dramatically* converted to Buddhism after seeing the suffering caused by the war since his Major Rock Edict 13 states that he became closer to the dhamma after the annexation of Kalinga.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] However, even if Ashoka converted to Buddhism *after* the war, epigraphic evidence suggests that his conversion was a *gradual* process rather than a dramatic event.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] According to Ashoka's Major Rock Edict 13, he conquered Kalinga 8 years after ascending to the throne.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The edict states that during his conquest of Kalinga, 100,000 men and animals were killed in action; many times that number "perished"; and 150,000 men and animals were carried away from Kalinga as captives.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Ashoka states that the repentance of these sufferings caused him to devote himself to the practice and propagation of dharma.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] He proclaims that he now considered the slaughter, death and deportation caused during the conquest of a country painful and deplorable; and that he considered the suffering caused to the religious people and householders even more deplorable.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] This edict has been inscribed at several places, including Erragudi, Girnar, Kalsi, Maneshra, Shahbazgarhi and Kandahar.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] However, it is omitted in Ashoka's inscriptions found in the Kalinga region, where the Rock Edicts 13 and 14 have been replaced by two separate edicts that make no mention of Ashoka's remorse.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] It is possible that Ashoka did not consider it politically appropriate to make such a confession to the people of Kalinga.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Another possibility is the Kalinga war and its consequences, as described in Ashoka's rock edicts, are "more imaginary than real".
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] This description is meant to impress those far removed from the scene, thus unable to verify its accuracy.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Ancient sources do not mention any other military activity of Ashoka, although the 16th-century writer Taranatha claims that Ashoka conquered the entire Jambudvipa.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] It was built by Ashoka to commemorate the enlightenment of the Buddha, about two hundred years before him.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Different sources give different accounts of Ashoka's conversion to Buddhism.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] According to Sri Lankan tradition, Ashoka's father, Bindusara, was a devotee of Brahmanism, and his mother Dharma was a devotee of Ajivikas.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The *Samantapasadika* states that Ashoka followed non-Buddhist sects during the first three years of his reign.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The Sri Lankan texts add that Ashoka was not happy with the behaviour of the Brahmins who received his alms daily.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] His courtiers produced some Ajivika and Nigantha teachers before him, but these also failed to impress him.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The *Dipavamsa* states that Ashoka invited several non-Buddhist religious leaders to his palace and bestowed great gifts upon them in the hope that they would answer a question posed by the king.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The text does not state what the question was but mentions that none of the invitees were able to answer it.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] One day, Ashoka saw a young Buddhist monk called Nigrodha (or Nyagrodha), who was looking for alms on a road in Pataliputra.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] He was the king's nephew, although the king was not aware of this: he was a posthumous son of Ashoka's eldest brother Sumana, whom Ashoka had killed during the conflict for the throne.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Ashoka was impressed by Nigrodha's tranquil and fearless appearance, and asked him to teach him his faith.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] In response, Nigrodha offered him a sermon on appamada (earnestness).
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Impressed by the sermon, Ashoka offered Nigrodha 400,000 silver coins and 8 daily portions of rice.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The king became a Buddhist upasaka, and started visiting the Kukkutarama shrine at Pataliputra.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] At the temple, he met the Buddhist monk Moggaliputta Tissa, and became more devoted to the Buddhist faith.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The veracity of this story is not certain.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] This legend about Ashoka's search for a worthy teacher may be aimed at explaining why Ashoka did not adopt Jainism, another major contemporary faith that advocates non-violence and compassion.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The legend suggests that Ashoka was not attracted to Buddhism because he was looking for such a faith; instead, he was in search of a competent spiritual teacher.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The Sri Lankan tradition adds that during his sixth regnal year, Ashoka's son Mahinda became a Buddhist monk, and his daughter became a Buddhist nun.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] A story in *Divyavadana* attributes Ashoka's conversion to the Buddhist monk Samudra, who was an ex-merchant from Shravasti.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] According to this account, Samudra was imprisoned in Ashoka's "Hell", but saved himself using his miraculous powers.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] When Ashoka heard about this, he visited the monk, and was further impressed by a series of miracles performed by the monk.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] A story in the *Ashokavadana* states that Samudra was a merchant's son, and was a 12-year-old boy when he met Ashoka; this account seems to be influenced by the Nigrodha story.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The *A-yu-wang-chuan* states that a 7-year-old Buddhist converted Ashoka.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Another story claims that the young boy ate 500 Brahmanas who were harassing Ashoka for being interested in Buddhism; these Brahmanas later miraculously turned into Buddhist bhikkus at the Kukkutarama monastery, which Ashoka visited.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Several Buddhist establishments existed in various parts of India by the time of Ashoka's ascension.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] It is not clear which branch of the Buddhist sangha influenced him, but the one at his capital Pataliputra is a good candidate.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Both *Mahavamsa* and *Ashokavadana* state that Ashoka constructed 84,000 stupas or viharas.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] According to the *Mahavamsa*, this activity took place during his fifth–seventh regnal years.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The *Ashokavadana* states that Ashoka collected seven out of the eight relics of Gautama Buddha, and had their portions kept in 84,000 boxes made of gold, silver, cat's eye, and crystal.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] He ordered the construction of 84,000 stupas throughout the earth, in towns that had a population of 100,000 or more.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] He told Elder Yashas, a monk at the Kukkutarama monastery, that he wanted these stupas to be completed on the same day.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Yashas stated that he would signal the completion time by eclipsing the sun with his hand.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] When he did so, the 84,000 stupas were completed at once.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The *Mahavamsa* states that Ashoka ordered construction of 84,000 viharas (monasteries) rather than the stupas to house the relics.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Like *Ashokavadana*, the *Mahavamsa* describes Ashoka's collection of the relics, but does not mention this episode in the context of the construction activities.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] It states that Ashoka decided to construct the 84,000 viharas when Moggaliputta Tissa told him that there were 84,000 sections of the Buddha's Dharma.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Ashoka himself began the construction of the Ashokarama vihara, and ordered subordinate kings to build the other viharas.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Ashokarama was completed by the miraculous power of Thera Indagutta, and the news about the completion of the 84,000 viharas arrived from various cities on the same day.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The pillars of Ashoka are a series of monolithic columns dispersed throughout the Indian subcontinent, erected—or at least inscribed with edicts—by the 3rd Mauryan Emperor Ashoka the Great, who reigned from c.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Ashoka used the expression *Dhaṃma thaṃbhā* (Dharma stambha), i.e.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] "pillars of the Dharma" to describe his own pillars.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] These pillars constitute important monuments of the architecture of India, most of them exhibiting the characteristic Mauryan polish.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Twenty of the pillars erected by Ashoka still survive, including those with inscriptions of his edicts.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Only a few with animal capitals survive of which seven complete specimens are known.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Two pillars were relocated by Firuz Shah Tughlaq to Delhi.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Several pillars were relocated later by Mughal Empire rulers, the animal capitals being removed.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Averaging between 12 and 15 m (40 and 50 ft) in height, and weighing up to 50 tons each, the pillars were dragged, sometimes hundreds of miles, to where they were erected.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The pillars were equipped with ornated capitals, many of which have been recovered to this day.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Ashoka's rock edicts suggest that during his eighth–ninth regnal years, he made a pilgrimage to the Bodhi Tree, started propagating dharma, and performed social welfare activities.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The welfare activities included establishment of medical treatment facilities for humans and animals; plantation of medicinal herbs; and digging of wells and plantation of trees along the roads.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] These activities were conducted in the neighbouring kingdoms, including those of the Cholas, the Pandyas, the Satiyaputras, Tamraparni, the Greek kingdom of Antiyoka.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The edicts also state that during his tenth–eleventh regnal years, Ashoka became closer to the Buddhist sangha, and went on a tour of the empire that lasted for at least 256 days.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] By his 12th regnal year, Ashoka had started inscribing edicts to propagate dharma, having ordered his officers (*rajjukas* and *pradesikas*) to tour their jurisdictions every five years for inspection and for preaching *dharma*.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] By the next year, he had set up the post of the *dharma-mahamatra*.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] During his 14th regnal year, he commissioned the enlargement of the stupa of Buddha Kanakamuni.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The Sri Lankan tradition presents a greater role for Ashoka in the Buddhist community.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] In this tradition, Ashoka starts feeding monks on a large scale.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] His lavish patronage to the state patronage leads to many fake monks joining the sangha.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The true Buddhist monks refuse to co-operate with these fake monks, and therefore, no uposatha ceremony is held for seven years.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The king attempts to eradicate the fake monks, but during this attempt, an over-zealous minister ends up killing some real monks.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The king then invites the elder monk Moggaliputta-Tissa, to help him expel non-Buddhists from the monastery founded by him at Pataliputra.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] 60,000 monks (bhikkhus) convicted of being heretical are de-frocked in the ensuing process.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The uposatha ceremony is then held, and Tissa subsequently organises the Third Buddhist council, during the 17th regnal year of Ashoka.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Tissa compiles *Kathavatthu*, a text that reaffirms Theravadin orthodoxy on several points.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The North Indian tradition makes no mention of these events, which has led to doubts about the historicity of the Third Buddhist council.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Richard Gombrich argues that the non-corroboration of this story by inscriptional evidence cannot be used to dismiss it as completely unhistorical, as several of Ashoka's inscriptions may have been lost.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Gombrich also argues that Asohka's inscriptions prove that he was interested in maintaining the "unanimity and purity" of the Sangha.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] For example, in his Minor Rock Edict 3, Ashoka recommends the members of the Sangha to study certain texts (most of which remain unidentified).
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Similarly, in an inscription found at Sanchi, Sarnath, and Kosam, Ashoka mandates that the dissident members of the sangha should be expelled, and expresses his desire to the Sangha remain united and flourish.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The 8th-century Buddhist pilgrim Yijing records another story about Ashoka's involvement in the Buddhist sangha.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] According to this story, the earlier king Bimbisara, who was a contemporary of the Gautama Buddha, once saw 18 fragments of a cloth and a stick in a dream.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The Buddha interpreted the dream to mean that his philosophy would be divided into 18 schools after his death, and predicted that a king called Ashoka would unite these schools over a hundred years later.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] In the Sri Lankan tradition, Moggaliputta-Tissa – who is patronised by Ashoka – sends out nine Buddhist missions to spread Buddhism in the "border areas" in c.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] This tradition does not credit Ashoka directly with sending these missions.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Each mission comprises five monks, and is headed by an elder.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] To Sri Lanka, he sent his own son Mahinda, accompanied by four other Theras – Itthiya, Uttiya, Sambala and Bhaddasala.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Next, with Moggaliputta-Tissa's help, Ashoka sent Buddhist missionaries to distant regions such as Kashmir, Gandhara, Himalayas, the land of the Yonas (Greeks), Maharashtra, Suvannabhumi, and Sri Lanka.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The tradition adds that during his 19th regnal year, Ashoka's daughter Sanghamitta went to Sri Lanka to establish an order of nuns, taking a sapling of the sacred Bodhi Tree with her.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The North Indian tradition makes no mention of these events.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Ashoka's own inscriptions also appear to omit any mention of these events, recording only one of his activities during this period: in his 19th regnal year, he donated the Khalatika Cave to ascetics to provide them a shelter during the rainy season.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Ashoka's Pillar Edicts suggest that during the next year, he made pilgrimage to Lumbini – the place of Buddha's birth, and to the stupa of the Buddha Kanakamuni.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The Rock Edict XIII states that Ashoka's won a "dhamma victory" by sending messengers to five kings and several other kingdoms.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Whether these missions correspond to the Buddhist missions recorded in the Buddhist chronicles is debated.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Indologist Etienne Lamotte argues that the "dhamma" missionaries mentioned in Ashoka's inscriptions were probably not Buddhist monks, as this "dhamma" was not same as "Buddhism".
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Moreover, the lists of destinations of the missions and the dates of the missions mentioned in the inscriptions do not tally the ones mentioned in the Buddhist legends.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Other scholars, such as Erich Frauwallner and Richard Gombrich, believe that the missions mentioned in the Sri Lankan tradition are historical.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] According to these scholars, a part of this story is corroborated by archaeological evidence: the *Vinaya Nidana* mentions names of five monks, who are said to have gone to the Himalayan region; three of these names have been found inscribed on relic caskets found at Bhilsa (near Vidisha).
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] These caskets have been dated to the early 2nd century BCE, and the inscription states that the monks are of the Himalayan school.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The missions may have set out from Vidisha in central India, as the caskets were discovered there, and as Mahinda is said to have stayed there for a month before setting out for Sri Lanka.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] According to Gombrich, the mission may have included representatives of other religions, and thus, Lamotte's objection about "dhamma" is not valid.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The Buddhist chroniclers may have decided not to mention these non-Buddhists, so as not to sideline Buddhism.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Frauwallner and Gombrich also believe that Ashoka was directly responsible for the missions, since only a resourceful ruler could have sponsored such activities.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The Sri Lankan chronicles, which belong to the Theravada school, exaggerate the role of the Theravadin monk Moggaliputta-Tissa in order to glorify their sect.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Some historians argue that Buddhism became a major religion because of Ashoka's royal patronage.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] However, epigraphic evidence suggests that the spread of Buddhism in north-western India and Deccan region was less because of Ashoka's missions, and more because of merchants, traders, landowners and the artisan guilds who supported Buddhist establishments.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] According to the 5th-century Buddhist legend *Ashokavadana*, Ashoka resorted to violence even after converting to Buddhism.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] According to the *Ashokavadana*, a non-Buddhist in Pundravardhana drew a picture showing the Buddha bowing at the feet of the Nirgrantha leader Jnatiputra.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The term nirgrantha ("free from bonds") was originally used for a pre-Jaina ascetic order, but later came to be used for Jaina monks.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] "Jnatiputra" is identified with Mahavira, 24th Tirthankara of Jainism.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] The legend states that on complaint from a Buddhist devotee, Ashoka issued an order to arrest the non-Buddhist artist, and subsequently, another order to kill all the Ajivikas in Pundravardhana.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Around 18,000 followers of the Ajivika sect were executed as a result of this order.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Sometime later, another Nirgrantha follower in Pataliputra drew a similar picture.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Ashoka burnt him and his entire family alive in their house.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] He also announced an award of one dinara to anyone who brought him the head of a Nirgrantha heretic.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] According to *Ashokavadana*, as a result of this order, his own brother was mistaken for a heretic and killed by a cowherd.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Ashoka realised his mistake, and withdrew the order.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] These stories of persecutions of rival sects by Ashoka appear to be fabrications arising out of sectarian propaganda.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p01] Additionally, these stories do not appear in the Jain texts, such as the *Parishishtaparvan* or *Theravali*, which mention Ashoka.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Various sources mention five consorts of Ashoka: Devi (or Vedisa-Mahadevi-Shakyakumari), Asandhimitra, Padmavati, Karuvaki and Tishyarakshita.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Karuvaki is the only queen of Ashoka known from his own inscriptions: she is mentioned in an edict inscribed on a pillar at Allahabad.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The inscription names her as the mother of prince Tivara, and orders the imperial officers (mahamattas) to record her religious and charitable donations.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] According to one theory, Tishyarakshita was the regnal name of Kaurvaki.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] According to the *Mahavamsa*, Ashoka's chief empress was Asandhimitta, who died four years before him.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] It states that she was born as Ashoka's empress because in a previous life, she directed a pratyekabuddha to a honey merchant (who was later reborn as Ashoka).
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Some later texts also state that she additionally gave the pratyekabuddha a piece of cloth made by her.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] These texts include the *Dasavatthuppakarana*, the so-called Cambodian or Extended *Mahavamsa* (possibly from 9th–10th centuries), and the *Trai Bhumi Katha* (15th century).
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] These texts narrate another story: one day, Ashoka mocked Asandhamitta was enjoying a tasty piece of sugarcane without having earned it through her karma.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Asandhamitta replied that all her enjoyments resulted from merit resulting from her own karma.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Ashoka then challenged her to prove this by procuring 60,000 robes as an offering for monks.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] At night, the guardian gods informed her about her past gift to the pratyekabuddha, and next day, she was able to miraculously procure the 60,000 robes.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] An impressed Ashoka makes her his favourite empress, and even offers to make her a sovereign ruler.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Asandhamitta refuses the offer, but still invokes the jealousy of Ashoka's 16,000 other women.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Ashoka proves her superiority by having 16,000 identical cakes baked with his imperial seal hidden in only one of them.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Each wife is asked to choose a cake, and only Asandhamitta gets the one with the imperial seal.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The *Trai Bhumi Katha* claims that it was Asandhamitta who encouraged her husband to become a Buddhist, and to construct 84,000 stupas and 84,000 viharas.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] According to *Mahavamsa*, after Asandhamitta's death, Tissarakkha became the chief empress.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The Ashokavadana does not mention Asandhamitta at all, but does mention Tissarakkha as Tishyarakshita.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The *Divyavadana* mentions another empress called Padmavati, who was the mother of the crown-prince Kunala.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] As mentioned above, according to the Sri Lankan tradition, Ashoka fell in love with Devi (or Vidisha-Mahadevi), as a prince in central India.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] After Ashoka's ascension to the throne, Devi chose to remain at Vidisha than move to the imperial capital Pataliputra.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] According to the *Mahavmsa*, Ashoka's chief empress was Asandhamitta, not Devi: the text does not talk of any connection between the two women, so it is unlikely that Asandhamitta was another name for Devi.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The Sri Lankan tradition uses the word *samvasa* to describe the relationship between Ashoka and Devi, which modern scholars variously interpret as sexual relations outside marriage, or co-habitation as a married couple.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Those who argue that Ashoka did not marry Devi argue that their theory is corroborated by the fact that Devi did not become Ashoka's chief empress in Pataliputra after his ascension.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The *Dipavamsa* refers to two children of Ashoka and Devi – Mahinda and Sanghamitta.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Tivara, the fourth son of Ashoka and Karuvaki, is the only of Ashoka's sons to be mentioned by name in the inscriptions.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] According to North Indian tradition, Ashoka had a second son named Kunala.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The Sri Lankan tradition mentions a son called Mahinda, who was sent to Sri Lanka as a Buddhist missionary; this son is not mentioned at all in the North Indian tradition.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The Chinese pilgrim Xuanzang states that Mahinda was Ashoka's younger brother (Vitashoka or Vigatashoka) rather than his illegitimate son.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The *Divyavadana* mentions the crown-prince Kunala alias Dharmavivardhana, who was a second son of Ashoka and empress Padmavati.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] According to Faxian, Dharmavivardhana was appointed as the governor of Gandhara.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The *Rajatarangini* mentions Jalauka as a third son of Ashoka.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] According to Sri Lankan tradition, Ashoka had a daughter named Sanghamitta, who became a Bhikkhunī.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Another source mentions that Ashoka had a daughter named Charumati, who married a kshatriya named Devapala.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] According to the *Ashokavadana*, Ashoka had an elder half-brother named Susima.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Bindusara and Ashoka seem to have extended the empire southwards.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The distribution of Ashoka's inscriptions suggests that his empire included almost the entire Indian subcontinent, except its southernmost parts.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The Rock Edicts 2 and 13 suggest that these southernmost parts were controlled by the Cholas, the Pandyas, the Keralaputras, and the Satiyaputras.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] In the north-west, Ashoka's empire extended into Afghanistan, to the east of the Seleucid Empire ruled by Antiochus II.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The capital of Ashoka's empire was Pataliputra in the Magadha region.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The Buddhist legends state that Ashoka converted to Buddhism, although this has been debated by a section of scholars.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The Minor Rock Edict 1 leaves no doubt that Ashoka was a follower of Buddhism.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] In this edict, he calls himself an upasaka (a lay follower of Buddhism) and a *sakya* (i.e.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Buddhist, after Gautama Buddha's title *Shakya-Muni*).
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] A legend in the Buddhist text *Vamsatthapakasini* states that an Ajivika ascetic invited to interpret a dream of Ashoka's mother had predicted that he would patronise Buddhism and destroy 96 heretical sects.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] However, such assertions are directly contradicted by Ashoka's own inscriptions.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Ashoka's edicts, such as the Rock Edicts 6, 7, and 12, emphasise tolerance of all sects.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Similarly, in his Rock Edict 12, Ashoka honours people of all faiths.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] In his inscriptions, Ashoka dedicates caves to non-Buddhist ascetics, and repeatedly states that both Brahmins and shramanas deserved respect.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] He also tells people "not to denigrate other sects, but to inform themselves about them".
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] In fact, there is no evidence that Buddhism was a state religion under Ashoka.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] None of Ashoka's extant edicts record his direct donations to the Buddhists.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] One inscription records donations by his Queen Karuvaki, while the emperor is known to have donated the Barabar Caves to the Ajivikas.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] There are some indirect references to his donations to Buddhists.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] For example, the Nigalisagar Pillar inscription records his enlargement of the Konakamana stupa.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Similarly, the Lumbini (Rumminidei) inscription states that he exempted the village of Buddha's birth from the land tax, and reduced the revenue tax to one-eighth.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Ashoka appointed the *dhamma-mahamatta* officers, whose duties included the welfare of various religious sects, including the Buddhist sangha, Brahmins, Ajivikas, and Nirgranthas.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The Rock Edicts 8 and 12, and the Pillar Edict 7, mandate donations to all religious sects.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Ashoka's Minor Rock Edict 1 contains the phrase "*amissā devā*".
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] According to one interpretation, the term "*amissā*" derives from the word "*amṛṣa*" ("false"), and thus, the phrase is a reference to Ashoka's belief in "true" and "false" gods.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] However, it is more likely that the term derives from the word "*amiśra*" ("not mingled"), and the phrase refers to celestial beings who did not mingle with humans.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The inscription claims that the righteousness generated by adoption of dhamma by the humans attracted even the celestial gods who did not mingle with humans.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Ashoka's various inscriptions suggest that he devoted himself to the propagation of "Dharma" (Pali: Dhamma), a term that refers to the teachings of Gautama Buddha in the Buddhist circles.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] However, Ashoka's own inscriptions do not mention Buddhist doctrines such as the Four Noble Truths or Nirvana.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The word "Dharma" has various connotations in the Indian religions, and can be generally translated as "law, duty, or righteousness".
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] In the Kandahar inscriptions of Ashoka, the word "Dharma" has been translated as eusebeia (Greek) and qsyt (Aramaic), which further suggests that his "Dharma" meant something more generic than Buddhism.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Modern scholars have variously understood this *dhamma* as a Buddhist lay ethic, a set of politico-moral ideas, a "sort of universal religion", or as an Ashokan innovation.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] On the other hand, it has also been interpreted as an *essentially political* ideology that sought to knit together a vast and diverse empire.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Ashoka instituted a new category of officers called the *dhamma-mahamattas*, who were tasked with the welfare of the aged, the infirm, the women and children, and various religious sects.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] They were also sent on diplomatic missions to the Hellenistic kingdoms of west Asia, in order to propagate the dhamma.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Historically, the image of Ashoka in the global Buddhist circles was based on legends (such as those mentioned in the *Ashokavadana*) rather than his rock edicts.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] This was because the Brahmi script in which these edicts were written was forgotten soon and remained undeciphered until its study by James Prinsep in the 19th century.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The writings of the Chinese Buddhist pilgrims such as Faxian and Xuanzang suggest that Ashoka's inscriptions mark the important sites associated with Gautama Buddha.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] These writers attribute Buddhism-related content to Ashoka's edicts, but this content does not match with the actual text of the inscriptions as determined by modern scholars after the decipherment of the Brahmi script.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] It is likely that the script was forgotten by the time of Faxian, who probably relied on local guides; these guides may have made up some Buddhism-related interpretations to gratify him, or may have themselves relied on faulty translations based on oral traditions.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Xuanzang may have encountered a similar situation, or may have taken the supposed content of the inscriptions from Faxian's writings.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] This theory is corroborated by the fact that some Brahmin scholars are known to have similarly come up with a fanciful interpretation of Ashoka pillar inscriptions, when requested to decipher them by the 14th-century Muslim Tughlaq emperor Firuz Shah Tughlaq.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] According to Shams-i Siraj's *Tarikh-i Firoz Shahi*, after the king had these pillar transported from Topra and Mirat to Delhi as war trophies, these Brahmins told him that the inscriptions prophesied that nobody would be able to remove the pillars except a king named Firuz.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Moreover, by this time, there were local traditions that attributed the erection of these pillars to the legendary hero Bhima.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] According to scholars such as Richard Gombrich, Ashoka's dharma shows Buddhist influence.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] For example, the Kalinga Separate Edict I seems to be inspired by Buddha's *Advice to Sigala* and his other sermons.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Ashoka's rock edicts declare that injuring living things is not good, and no animal should be slaughtered for sacrifice.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] However, he did not prohibit common cattle slaughter or beef eating.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] He imposed a ban on killing of "all four-footed creatures that are neither useful nor edible", and of specific animal species including several birds, certain types of fish and bulls among others.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] He also banned killing of female goats, sheep and pigs that were nursing their young; as well as their young up to the age of six months.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] He also banned killing of all fish and castration of animals during certain periods such as Chaturmasa and Uposatha.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Ashoka also abolished the imperial hunting of animals and restricted the slaying of animals for food in the imperial residence.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] As Ashoka's edicts forbade both the killing of wild animals and the destruction of forests, he is seen by some modern environmental historians as an early embodiment of that environmental ethos.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] It is well known that Ashoka sent *dütas* or emissaries to convey messages or letters, written or oral (rather both), to various people.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The VIth Rock Edict about "oral orders" reveals this.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] There is obvious and undeniable trace of cultural contact through the adoption of the Kharosthi script, and the idea of installing inscriptions might have travelled with this script, as Achaemenid influence is seen in some of the formulations used by Ashoka in his inscriptions.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] This indicates to us that Ashoka was indeed in contact with other cultures, and was an active part in mingling and spreading new cultural ideas beyond his own immediate walls.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] by name, as recipients of his teachings.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Dionysius is reported to have been such a Greek ambassador at the court of Ashoka, sent by Ptolemy II Philadelphus, who himself is mentioned in the Edicts of Ashoka as a recipient of the Buddhist proselytism of Ashoka.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Some Hellenistic philosophers, such as Hegesias of Cyrene, who probably lived under the rule of King Magas, one of the supposed recipients of Buddhist emissaries from Ashoka, are sometimes thought to have been influenced by Buddhist teachings.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The Greeks in India even seem to have played an active role in the propagation of Buddhism, as some of the emissaries of Ashoka, such as Dharmaraksita, are described in Pali sources as leading Greek (Yona) Buddhist monks, active in spreading Buddhism (the *Mahavamsa*, XII).
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Some Greeks (Yavana) may have played an administrative role in the territories ruled by Ashoka.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The Girnar inscription of Rudradaman records that during the rule of Ashoka, a Yavana Governor was in charge in the area of Girnar, Gujarat, mentioning his role in the construction of a water reservoir.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] It is thought that Ashoka's palace at Patna was modelled after the Achaemenid palace of Persepolis.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Buddhist legends mention stories about Ashoka's past lives.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] According to a *Mahavamsa* story, Ashoka, Nigrodha and Devnampiya Tissa were brothers in a previous life.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] In that life, a pratyekabuddha was looking for honey to cure another, sick pratyekabuddha.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] A woman directed him to a honey shop owned by the three brothers.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Ashoka generously donated honey to the pratyekabuddha, and wished to become the sovereign ruler of Jambudvipa for this act of merit.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The woman wished to become his queen, and was reborn as Ashoka's wife Asandhamitta.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Later Pali texts credit her with an additional act of merit: she gifted the pratyekabuddha a piece of cloth made by her.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] These texts include the *Dasavatthuppakarana*, the so-called Cambodian or Extended *Mahavamsa* (possibly from 9th to 10th centuries), and the *Trai Bhumi Katha* (15th century).
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] According to an *Ashokavadana* story, Ashoka was born as Jaya in a prominent family of Rajagriha.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] When he was a little boy, he gave the Gautama Buddha dirt imagining it to be food.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The Buddha approved of the donation, and Jaya declared that he would become a king by this act of merit.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The text also state that Jaya's companion Vijaya was reborn as Ashoka's prime-minister Radhagupta.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] In the later life, the Buddhist monk Upagupta tells Ashoka that his rough skin was caused by the impure gift of dirt in the previous life.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Some later texts repeat this story, without mentioning the negative implications of gifting dirt; these texts include Kumaralata's *Kalpana-manditika*, Aryashura's *Jataka-mala*, and the *Maha-karma-vibhaga*.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The Chinese writer Pao Ch'eng's *Shih chia ju lai ying hua lu* asserts that an insignificant act like gifting dirt could not have been meritorious enough to cause Ashoka's future greatness.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Instead, the text claims that in another past life, Ashoka commissioned a large number of Buddha statues as a king, and this act of merit caused him to become a great emperor in the next life.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The 14th-century Pali-language fairy tale *Dasavatthuppakarana* (possibly from c.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] 14th century) combines the stories about the merchant's gift of honey, and the boy's gift of dirt.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] It narrates a slightly different version of the *Mahavamsa* story, stating that it took place before the birth of the Gautama Buddha.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] It then states that the merchant was reborn as the boy who gifted dirt to the Buddha; however, in this case, the Buddha gave the dirt to Ānanda, his attendant, to create plaster from the dirt, which was used repair cracks in the monastery walls.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Ashoka's last dated inscription - the Pillar Edict 4 is from his 26th regnal year.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The only source of information about Ashoka's later years are the Buddhist legends.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The Sri Lankan tradition states that Ashoka's empress Asandhamitta died during his 29th regnal year, and in his 32nd regnal year, his wife Tissarakkha was given the title of empress.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Both *Mahavamsa* and *Ashokavadana* state that Ashoka extended favours and attention to the Bodhi Tree, and a jealous Tissarakkha mistook "Bodhi" to be a mistress of Ashoka.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] She then used black magic to make the tree wither.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] According to the *Ashokavadana*, she hired a sorceress to do the job, and when Ashoka explained that "Bodhi" was the name of a tree, she had the sorceress heal the tree.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] According to the *Mahavamsa*, she completely destroyed the tree, during Ashoka's 34th regnal year.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The *Ashokavadana* states that Tissarakkha (called "Tishyarakshita" here) made sexual advances towards Ashoka's son Kunala, but Kunala rejected her.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Subsequently, Ashoka granted Tissarakkha emperorship for seven days, and during this period, she tortured and blinded Kunala.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Ashoka then threatened to "tear out her eyes, rip open her body with sharp rakes, impale her alive on a spit, cut off her nose with a saw, cut out her tongue with a razor." Kunala regained his eyesight miraculously, and pleaded for mercy for the empress, but Ashoka had her executed.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Kshemendra's *Avadana-kalpa-lata* also narrates this legend, but seeks to improve Ashoka's image by stating that he forgave the empress after Kunala regained his eyesight.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] According to the Sri Lankan tradition, Ashoka died during his 37th regnal year, which suggests that he died around 232 BCE.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] According to the *Ashokavadana*, the emperor fell severely ill during his last days.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] He started using state funds to make donations to the Buddhist sangha, prompting his ministers to deny him access to the state treasury.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Ashoka then started donating his personal possessions, but was similarly restricted from doing so.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] On his deathbed, his only possession was the half of a myrobalan fruit, which he offered to the sangha as his final donation.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Such legends encourage generous donations to the *sangha* and highlight the role of the emperorship in supporting the Buddhist faith.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Legend states that during his cremation, his body burned for seven days and nights.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Besides the various stupas attributed to Ashoka, the pillars erected by him survive at various places in the Indian subcontinent.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Ashoka is often credited with the beginning of stone architecture in India, dedicated to Buddhism, possibly following the introduction of stone-building techniques by the Greeks after Alexander the Great.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Before Ashoka's time, buildings were probably built in non-permanent material, such as wood, bamboo or thatch.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Ashoka may have rebuilt his palace in Pataliputra by replacing wooden material by stone, and may also have used the help of foreign craftmen.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Ashoka also innovated by using the permanent qualities of stone for his written edicts, as well as his pillars with Buddhist symbolism.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The Brahmi script appeared in India around the 3rd century BCE in a fully developed form.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Ashoka may have been the inventor of the new script, which he then used extensively for his inscriptions, but this remains an unresolved question.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] In contrast, multiple authors reject the idea of foreign influence.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] In the following millennia, most South Asian scripts were then derived from the Ashokan Brahmi script.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The edicts of Ashoka are a collection of 33 inscriptions on the Pillars of Ashoka, as well as boulders and cave walls, issued during his reign.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] These inscriptions are dispersed throughout modern-day Pakistan and India, and represent the first tangible evidence of Buddhism.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The edicts describe in detail the first wide expansion of Buddhism through the sponsorship of one of the most powerful kings of Indian history, offering more information about Ashoka's proselytism, moral precepts, religious precepts and his notions of social and animal welfare.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Before Ashoka, the royal communications appear to have been written on perishable materials such as palm leaves, birch barks, cotton cloth, and possibly wooden boards.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] While Ashoka's administration would have continued to use these materials, Ashoka also had his messages inscribed on rock edicts.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Ashoka probably got the idea of putting up these inscriptions from the neighbouring Achaemenid empire.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] It is likely that Ashoka's messages were also inscribed on more perishable materials, such as wood, and sent to various parts of the empire.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Most of Ashoka's inscriptions are written in a mixture of various Prakrit dialects, in the Brahmi script.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Several of Ashoka's inscriptions appear to have been set up near towns, on important routes, and at places of religious significance.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Many of the inscriptions have been discovered in hills, rock shelters, and places of local significance.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Various theories have been put forward about why Ashoka or his officials chose such places, including that they were centres of megalithic cultures, were regarded as sacred spots in Ashoka's time, or that their physical grandeur may be symbolic of spiritual dominance.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Ashoka's inscriptions have not been found at major cities of the Maurya empire, such as Pataliputra, Vidisha, Ujjayini, and Taxila.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] It is possible that many of these inscriptions are lost; the 7th-century Chinese pilgrim Xuanzang refers to some of Ashoka's pillar edicts, which have not been discovered by modern researchers.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] It appears that Ashoka dispatched every message to his provincial governors, who in turn, relayed it to various officials in their territory.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] For example, the Minor Rock Edict 1 appears in several versions at multiple places: all the versions state that Ashoka issued the proclamation while on a tour, having spent 256 days on tour.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The number 256 indicates that the message was dispatched simultaneously to various places.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Three versions of a message, found at edicts in the neighbouring places in Karnataka (Brahmagiri, Siddapura, and Jatinga-Rameshwara), were sent from the southern province's capital Suvarnagiri to various places.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] All three versions contain the same message, preceded by an initial greeting from the *arya-putra* (presumably Ashoka's son and the provincial governor) and the *mahamatras* (officials) in Suvarnagiri.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The caduceus appears as a symbol of the punch-marked coins of the Maurya Empire in India, in the 3rd–2nd century BCE.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Numismatic research suggests that this symbol was the symbol of Emperor Ashoka, his personal "Mudra".
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] This symbol was not used on the pre-Mauryan punch-marked coins, but only on coins of the Maurya period, together with the three arched-hill symbol, the "peacock on the hill", the triskelis and the Taxila mark.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Ashokan capitals were highly realistic and used a characteristic polished finish, Mauryan polish, giving a shiny appearance to the stone surface.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Lion Capital of Ashoka, the capital of one of the pillars erected by Ashoka features a carving of a spoked wheel, known as the Ashoka Chakra.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] This wheel represents the wheel of Dhamma set in motion by the Gautama Buddha, and appears on the flag of modern India.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] This capital also features sculptures of lions, which appear on the seal of India.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Ashoka had almost been forgotten until the 19th century, when James Prinsep contributed in the revelation of historical sources.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] After deciphering the Brahmi script, Prinsep had originally identified the "Priyadasi" of the inscriptions he found with the King of Ceylon Devanampiya Tissa.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Another important historian was British archaeologist John Hubert Marshall, who was director-general of the Archaeological Survey of India.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] His main interests were Sanchi and Sarnath, in addition to Harappa and Mohenjodaro.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Sir Alexander Cunningham, a British archaeologist and army engineer, and often known as the father of the Archaeological Survey of India, unveiled heritage sites like the Bharhut Stupa, Sarnath, Sanchi, and the Mahabodhi Temple.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Mortimer Wheeler, a British archaeologist, also exposed Ashokan historical sources, especially the Taxila.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The use of Buddhist sources in reconstructing the life of Ashoka has had a strong influence on perceptions of Ashoka, as well as the interpretations of his edicts.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Building on traditional accounts, early scholars regarded Ashoka as a primarily Buddhist monarch who underwent a conversion from the Vedic religion to Buddhism and was actively engaged in sponsoring and supporting the Buddhist monastic institution.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Some scholars have tended to question this assessment.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] For example, Amartya Sen writes, "The Indian Emperor Ashoka in the third century BCE presented many political inscriptions in favor of tolerance and individual freedom, both as a part of state policy and in the relation of different people to each other".
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] However, the edicts alone strongly *indicate* that he was a Buddhist.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] In one edict he belittles rituals, and he banned Vedic animal sacrifices; these strongly suggest that he at least did not look to the Vedic tradition for guidance.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Furthermore, many edicts are expressed to Buddhists alone; in one, Ashoka declares himself to be an "upasaka", and in another he demonstrates a close familiarity with Buddhist texts.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] He erected rock pillars at Buddhist holy sites, but did not do so for the sites of other religions.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] He also used the word "dhamma" to refer to qualities of the heart that underlie moral action; this was an exclusively Buddhist use of the word.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] However, he used the word more in the spirit than as a strict code of conduct.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Thapar writes, "His dhamma did not derive from divine inspiration, even if its observance promised heaven.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] It was more in keeping with the ethic conditioned by the logic of given situations.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] His logic of Dhamma was intended to influence the conduct of categories of people, in relation to each other.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Especially where they involved unequal relationships." Finally, he promotes ideals that correspond to the first three steps of the Buddha's graduated discourse.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Much of the knowledge about Ashoka comes from the several inscriptions that he had carved on pillars and rocks throughout the empire.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] All his inscriptions present him as compassionate and loving.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] In the Kalinga rock edits, he addresses his people as his "children" and mentions that as a father he desires their good.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Beckwith — whose theories are not accepted by mainstream scholarship — Ashoka, whose name only appears in the Minor Rock Edicts, is not the same as king Piyadasi, or *Devanampiya* Piyadasi (i.e.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] "Beloved of the Gods Piyadasi", "Beloved of the Gods" being a fairly widespread title for "King"), who is named as the author of the Major Pillar Edicts and the Major Rock Edicts.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Also, the geographical spread of his inscription shows that Piyadasi ruled a vast Empire, contiguous with the Seleucid Empire in the West.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] On the contrary, for Beckwith, Ashoka was a later king of the 1st–2nd century CE, whose name only appears explicitly in the Minor Rock Edicts and allusively in the Minor Pillar Edicts, and who does mention the Buddha and the Sangha, explicitly promoting Buddhism.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The name "Priyadarsi" does occur in two of the minor edicts (Gujarra and Bairat), but Beckwith again considers them as later fabrications.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The minor inscriptions cover a very different and much smaller geographical area, clustering in Central India.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] According to Beckwith, the inscriptions of this later Ashoka were typical of the later forms of "normative Buddhism", which are well attested from inscriptions and Gandhari manuscripts dated to the turn of the millennium, and around the time of the Kushan Empire.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The quality of the inscriptions of this Ashoka is significantly lower than the quality of the inscriptions of the earlier Piyadasi.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] However, many of Beckwith's methodologies and interpretations concerning early Buddhism, inscriptions, and archaeological sites have been criticized by other scholars, such as Johannes Bronkhorst and Osmund Bopearachchi.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] After Ashoka's death, the Maurya dynasty declined rapidly.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The various Puranas provide different details about Ashoka's successors, but all agree that they had relatively short reigns.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] The empire seems to have weakened, fragmented, and suffered an invasion from the Bactrian Greeks.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Raychaudhuri, have argued that Ashoka's pacifism undermined the "military backbone" of the Maurya empire.
[src:ashoka/ashoka-p02] Others, such as Thapar, have suggested that the extent and impact of his pacifism have been "grossly exaggerated".
